ck, forward\n* [[1947 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1947]]\u2013 Charles B. Black, forward\n* [[1950 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1950]]\u2013 [[Clyde Lovellette]], center\n* [[1953 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1953]]\u2013 [[B. H. Born]], center\n* [[1961 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1961]]\u2013 [[Bill Bridges (basketball)|Bill Bridges]], forward\n* [[1962 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1962]]\u2013 Jerry Gardner, guard\n* [[1965 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1965]]\u2013 Walt Wesley, center\n* [[1966 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1966]]\u2013 Walt Wesley, center\n* [[1968 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1968]]\u2013 [[Jo Jo White]], guard\n* [[1969 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1969]]\u2013 Jo Jo White, guard\n{{col-3}}\n* [[1970 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1970]]\u2013 [[Dave Robisch]], forward\n* [[1971 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1971]]\u2013 Dave Robisch, forward\n* [[1972 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1972]]\u2013 Bud Stallworth, forward\n* [[1981 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1981]]\u2013 [[Darnell Valentine]], guard\n* [[1986 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1986]]\u2013 [[Danny Manning]], forward\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Academic All-Americans===\n* 1971 \u2013 Bud Stallworth\n* 1974 \u2013 Tom Kivisto\n* 1977 \u2013 Cris Barnthouse & Ken Koenigs\n* 1978 \u2013 Ken Koenigs\n* 1979 \u2013 Darnell Valentine\n* 1980 \u2013 Darnell Valentine\n* 1981 \u2013 Darnell Valentine\n* 1982 \u2013 David Magley\n* 1996 \u2013 Jacque Vaughn\n* 1997 \u2013 Jacque Vaughn\u2020 & Jerod Haase\n* 1999 \u2013 Ryan Robertson\n* 2010 \u2013 Cole Aldrich\u2020\n* 2011 \u2013 [[Tyrel Reed]]\n\n\u2020 indicates Academic All-American of the Year\n\n===National Player of the Year awards===\n* 1923 \u2013 Paul Endacott ([[Helms Foundation Player of the Year|Helms Foundation]])\n* 1924 \u2013 [[Charlie T. Black]] (Helms Foundation)\n* 1952 \u2013 Clyde Lovellette (Helms Foundation)\n* 1988 \u2013 Danny Manning ([[John R. Wooden Award|Wooden]], [[NABC Player of the Year|NABC]], [[Naismith College Player of the Year|Naismith]])\n* 2002 \u2013 Drew Gooden (NABC)\n* 2003 \u2013 Nick Collison (NABC)\n* 2017 \u2013 Frank Mason III (Consensus)<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite web|title=Kansas' Frank Mason III is AP Player of the Year, unanimous All-America selection|url=http://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/kansas-frank-mason-iii-is-ap-player-of-the-year-unanimous-all-america-selection/|website=CBSSports.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Kansas' Frank Mason III is Sporting News college basketball Player of the Year|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/ncaa-basketball/news/frank-mason-iii-sporting-news-2016-17-college-basketball-player-of-the-year/4swrmhkjz2ue14vch3iylgnt3|website=SportingNews.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=USA TODAY Sports player of the year: Kansas' Frank Mason III|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaab/2017/03/07/player-of-the-year-frank-mason-iii-kansas/98801864/|website=USAToday.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mason Wins Oscar Robertson Trophy|url=http://www.big12sports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=10410&ATCLID=211539593|website=Big12Sports.con}},</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mason awarded Naismith Trophy|url=http://kuathletics.com/news/2017/4/2/mens-basketball-mason-awarded-naismith-trophy.aspx|website=KUAthletics.com}},</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=KU\u2019s Frank Mason adds to award haul with NABC player of year|url=http://www.kansascity.com/sports/college/big-12/university-of-kansas/article142336589.html|website=KansasCity.com}}</ref><ref name=\"Wooden\">{{cite web|title=Kansas' Frank Mason wins Wooden award as nation's top player|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/19106290/frank-mason-iii-kansas-wins-john-r-wooden-award-nation-top-player|website=ESPN.com}}</ref>\n\n===McDonald's All-Americans===\nThe 49 [[McDonald's All-American]]s listed below have signed with Kansas.<ref>[http://www.mcdonaldsallamerican.com/Alumni_Boys%202009.pdf McDonald's All-American Alumni]</ref> An asterisk, \"*\", Indicates player did not finish his college career at Kansas. A cross, \"\u2020\", indicates player did not begin his college career at Kansas. The 2015 game had the most future Jayhawks playing in the game with four, however, two players transferred to Kansas and one transferred out of Kansas.\n;1970\u20131999\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* 1977 \u2013 [[Darnell Valentine]]\n* 1978 \u2013 [[Tony Guy]]\n* 1979 \u2013 Ricky Ross*\n* 1981 \u2013 [[Greg Dreiling]]\u2020\n* 1982 \u2013 [[Kerry Boagni]]*\n* 1984 \u2013 [[Danny Manning]]\n* 1985 \u2013 [[Rick Calloway]]\u2020\n* 1986 \u2013 [[Mark Randall (basketball)|Mark Randall]]\n* 1987 \u2013 Mike Maddox\n{{col-2}}\n* 1990 \u2013 [[Darrin Hancock]]\u2020\n* 1991 \u2013 Calvin Rayford & [[Ben Davis (basketball)|Ben Davis]]*\n* 1993 \u2013 [[Jacque Vaughn]]\n* 1994 \u2013 [[Raef LaFrentz]]\n* 1995 \u2013 [[Ryan Robertson]] & [[Paul Pierce]]\n* 1996 \u2013 Lester Earl\u2020\n* 1997 \u2013 [[Kenny Gregory]] & [[Eric Chenowith]]\n* 1998 \u2013 [[Jeff Boschee]]\n* 1999 \u2013 [[Nick Collison]]\n{{col-end}}\n;2000\u20132019\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* 2001 \u2013 [[Wayne Simien]] & [[Aaron Miles (basketball)|Aaron Miles]]\n* 2003 \u2013 [[J. R. Giddens]]* & [[David Padgett]]*\n* 2005 \u2013 [[Micah Downs]]*, [[Mario Chalmers]] & [[Julian Wright]]\n* 2006 \u2013 [[Sherron Collins]] & [[Darrell Arthur]]\n* 2007 \u2013 [[Cole Aldrich]]\n* 2009 \u2013 [[Xavier Henry]]\n* 2010 \u2013 [[Josh Selby]]\n{{col-2}}\n* 2012 \u2013 [[Perry Ellis (basketball)|Perry Ellis]]\n* 2013 \u2013 [[Wayne Selden, Jr.]] & [[Andrew Wiggins]]\n* 2014 \u2013 [[Cliff Alexander]] & [[Kelly Oubre]]\n* 2015 \u2013 Carlton Bragg*, [[Cheick Diallo]], [[Malik Newman]]\u2020 & [[Dedric Lawson]]\u2020 \n* 2016 \u2013 [[Udoka Azubuike]] & [[Josh Jackson (basketball)|Josh Jackson]]\n* 2017 \u2013 [[Billy Preston (basketball)|Billy Preston]]\n* 2018 \u2013 David McCormack, [[Quentin Grimes]] & [[Devon Dotson]]\n{{col-end}}\n;2020\u2013present \n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* 2020 \u2013 Bryce Thompson\n\n===Jayhawk basketball players notable in other fields===\n* [[Bob Dole]] \u2013 Politician \u2013 1941\u20131945\n\n===Retired jerseys===\nThirty-one players have had their jersey retired by Kansas. One former announcer, Max Falkenstien, is honored with the retired jerseys as well. His number 60 was chosen because that was the number of years he was the radio announcer for the Jayhawks. KU only retires the jerseys, and not the numbers, of past basketball players. Eight players honored played on one of KU's 5 championship teams. [[Charlie T. Black]] and [[Paul Endacott]] are the only two players with their jerseys retired to play on two championship teams. Four players from the 2008 Championship have their jersey retired, which is the most players honored to be on a roster in any single season in Kansas basketball history.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Kansas Jayhawks|border=0|color=white}}\"| '''Kansas Jayhawks retired jerseys'''\n|-\n!  style=\"width:40px; {{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Kansas Jayhawks|border=0|color=white}}\"| No.\n!  style=\"width:150px; {{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Kansas Jayhawks|border=0|color=white}}\"|Player\n!  style=\"width:40px; {{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Kansas Jayhawks|border=0|color=white}}\"|Position\n!  style=\"width:150px; {{CollegeSecondaryStyle|Kansas Jayhawks|border=0|color=white}}\"|Career\n|-\n| '''0''' || [[Drew Gooden]]|| [[Forward (basketball)|F]] || 2000\u201302\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | '''4''' || [[Nick Collison]] || [[Forward (basketball)|F]] || 2000\u201303\n|-\n|[[Sherron Collins]]^\n|[[Point guard|G]]\n|2006\u201310\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| '''5''' || [[Fred Pralle]] || [[Guard (basketball)|G]] ||1936\u201338\n|-\n| [[Howard Engleman]] || [[Forward (basketball)|F]] || 1939\u201341\n|-\n| '''7''' || [[Tusten Ackerman]]\u2020 || [[Center (basketball)|