g\n| url =http://www.amlo.org.mx/\n| accessdate=11 July 2006\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060714075933/http://www.amlo.org.mx/| archivedate= 14 July 2006 |url-status = live|language=es}}\n*{{cite web\n |title       = Unofficial campaign site\n |work        = Lopez-obrador.com.mx\n |url         = http://www.Lopez-obrador.com.mx/\n |accessdate  = 11 July 2006\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20060714175221/http://www.lopez-obrador.com.mx/\n |archivedate = 14 July 2006\n |url-status = dead\n |language    = es\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n*{{cite web\n| title =Extended biography by CIDOB Foundation\n| work =cidob-org\n| url =http://www.cidob.org/es/documentacion/biografias_lideres_politicos/america_del_norte/mexico/andres_manuel_lopez_obrador\n| accessdate=1 January 2007\n|language=es}}\n*{{Cite web\n| title =Collection of articles from Council on Hemispheric Affairs concerning Mexican politics\n| url =http://www.coha.org/category/mexico/}}\n*{{cite journal\n |title=Zapatista leader blasts L\u00f3pez \n |journal=El Universal \n |id= \n |url=http://estadis.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/126320.html \n |language=es \n |url-status = dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050622020711/http://estadis.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/126320.html \n |archivedate=22 June 2005 \n}}\n*{{cite web\n |title=Redes Ciudadanas Baja California \n |work=amlo.org \n |url=http://www.amlobc.com/ \n |accessdate=11 July 2006 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060709042226/http://www.amlobc.com/ \n |archivedate=9 July 2006 \n |url-status = dead\n |language=es \n}}\n*{{C-SPAN|114582}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rosario Robles]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of heads of government of Mexico City|Head of Government of Mexico City]]|years=2000\u20132005}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Alejandro Encinas Rodr\u00edguez]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Enrique Pe\u00f1a Nieto]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Mexico]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Porfirio Mu\u00f1oz Ledo]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Party of the Democratic Revolution|Leader of the Party of the Democratic Revolution]]|years=1996\u20131999}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Pablo G\u00f3mez \u00c1lvarez]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mart\u00ed Batres]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[National Regeneration Movement|President of the National Regeneration Movement]]|years=2012\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Yeidckol Polevnsky Gurwitz]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Cuauht\u00e9moc C\u00e1rdenas]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Party of the Democratic Revolution]] nominee for<br />President of Mexico|years=[[2006 Mexican general election|2006]], [[2012 Mexican general election|2012]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ricardo Anaya]]}}\n|-\n{{s-new|party}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[National Regeneration Movement]] nominee for<br />President of Mexico|years=[[2018 Mexican general election|2018]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Presidents of Mexico}}\n{{List of Current Heads of State of G20}}\n{{Current G20 Leaders}}\n{{Current APEC Leaders}}\n{{Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador Cabinet}}\n{{Heads of Government of the Mexican Federal District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lopez Obrador, Andres Manuel}}\n[[Category:Mexican socialists]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mexican politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Mexican politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Heads of Government of Mexico City]]\n[[Category:Institutional Revolutionary Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Party of the Democratic Revolution politicians]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2006 Mexican presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2012 Mexican presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2018 Mexican presidential election]]\n[[Category:Democratic socialists]]\n[[Category:Mexican Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Mexican Christian socialists]]\n[[Category:Mexican democracy activists]]\n[[Category:Mexican Marxists]]\n[[Category:Mexican nationalists]]\n[[Category:Mexican people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:Mexican social democrats]]\n[[Category:National Autonomous University of Mexico alumni]]\n[[Category:National Regeneration Movement politicians]]\n[[Category:Nonviolence advocates]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Tabasco]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Party of the Democratic Revolution]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Mexico]]\n[[Category:2018 in Mexican politics]]\n[[Category:2019 in Mexican politics]]\n[[Category:2020 in Mexican politics]]\n", "name_user": "Drevolt", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andr%C3%A9s_Manuel_L%C3%B3pez_Obrador"}
{"title_page": "2012 Nuevo Laredo massacres", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title       = 2012 Nuevo Laredo massacres\n| partof      = [[Mexican Drug War]]\n| image       =\n| image_size  = 270px\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Agency image of the hanging cadavers\n| map         =\n| map_size    =\n| map_alt     =\n| map_caption =\n| location    = [[Nuevo Laredo]], [[Tamaulipas]], Mexico\n| target      = \n| fatalities = Unknown\n| coordinates = {{coord|27|29|10|N|99|30|25|W|source:kolossus-nlwiki}}\n| date        = 2012\n| time        = \n| timezone    = \n| type        = [[wikt:turf war|Turf war]]\n| injuries    = Unknown\n| victim      =\n| perps       = [[Sinaloa Cartel]]<br>[[Los Zetas]]<br>[[Gulf Cartel]]\n| perp        =\n| perpetrators= \n| perpetrator = \n| susperps    = \n| susperp     = \n| weapons     = \n| numparts    =\n| numpart     =\n| dfens       =\n| dfen        =\n| footage     =\n| motive      = \n}}\n{{Campaignbox Mexican Drug War}}\nThe '''2012 Nuevo Laredo massacres''' were a series of mass murder attacks between the allied [[Sinaloa Cartel]] and [[Gulf Cartel]] against [[Los Zetas]] in the border city of [[Nuevo Laredo]], [[Tamaulipas]], across the U.S.-Mexico border from [[Laredo, Texas]]. The drug-violence in Nuevo Laredo began back in 2003, when the city was controlled by the [[Gulf Cartel]]. Most media reports that write about the [[Mexican Drug War]], however, point to 2006 as the start of the drug war.<ref name=ioangrillo2004>{{cite book|last=[[Ioan Grillo]]|title=El Narco: The Bloody Rise of Mexican Drug Cartels|year=2012|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Publishing]]|isbn=1408824337|pages=336|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WI08rbJt0oQC&pg=PA94&dq=nuevo+laredo+2004&hl=en&sa=X&ei=GeatT8mON6fD2QWZtrzqCA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=nuevo%20laredo%202004&f=false}}</ref> That year is a convenient historical marker because that's when [[Felipe Calder\u00f3n]] took office and carried out an aggressive approach against the cartels. But authors like [[Ioan Grillo]] and Sylvia Longmire note that Mexico's drug war actually began at the end of [[Vicente Fox]]'s administration in 2004,<ref name=ioangrillo2004/> when the first major battle took place in Nuevo Laredo between the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] and [[Los Zetas]], who at that time worked as the armed wing of the [[Gulf Cartel]].<ref name=ioangrillo2004/><ref name=longmire2004>{{cite news|last=Longmire|first=Sylvia|title=BOOK REVIEW: \"El Narco: Inside Mexico's Criminal Insurgency,\" by Ioan Grillo|url=http://borderviolenceanalysis.typepad.com/mexicos_drug_war/2011/06/book-review-el-narco-by-ioan-grillo.html|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=Mexico's drug war|date=29 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nWhen [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], the former leader of the [[Gulf Cartel]], was arrested in 2003, the [[Sinaloa Cartel]], sensing weakness, tried to move in on Nuevo Laredo, unleashing a bloody battle.<ref name=aploszetas>{{cite news|title=At least 23 people killed in Mexican border city|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5jaEGLgtDqnAWnn89LL9L3Gy48MRQ?docId=17f3dd6b31ca4e56a5e8c9e57a9d375e|accessdate=6 May 2012|agency=Associated Press|date=5 May 2012}}</ref> [[Los Zetas]], however, were successful in expelling the Sinaloa organization out of Nuevo Laredo, and have ruled the city \"with fear\" ever since.<ref name=aploszetas/> Nevertheless, the Gulf cartel and Los Zetas broke relations in early 2010, worsening the violence across northeast Mexico.<ref>{{cite news|title=23 people killed, most decapitated, in Mexican city near US border|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/at-least-23-people-killed-in-mexican-border-city-of-nuevo-laredo-scene-of-drug-cartel-war/2012/05/04/gIQA715J2T_story.html|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|date=4 May 2012}}</ref> The cartels are fighting for control of the corridor in Nuevo Laredo that leads into [[Interstate 35]], one of the most lucrative routes for drug traffickers.<ref name=dallasnews>{{cite news|title=23 killed in Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/news/nationworld/mexico/20120504-23-killed-in-nuevo-laredo.ece|accessdate=6 May 2012|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|date=4 May 2012}}</ref> Nuevo Laredo is a lucrative drug corridor because of the large volume of trucks that pass through the area, and the multiple (exploitable) ports of entry.<ref name=longmirecartel>{{cite news|last=Longmire|first=Sylvia|title=Nuevo Laredo heats up as Sinaloa-Zetas conflict leaves 23 dead.|url=http://borderviolenceanalysis.typepad.com/mexicos_drug_war/2012/05/nuevo-laredo-heats-up-as-sinaloa-zetas-conflict-leaves-23-dead.html|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=Mexico's drug war|date=5 May 2012}}</ref> Over 40% of all cargo crossings from Mexico to the United States crosses through the border checkpoints in Nuevo Laredo.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fourteen bodies found in eastern Mexico: officials|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jkZglpMB2jNLQwdlC81JxRXmuBVw?docId=CNG.b2371552eed6d000aa85ebc4c2e4bc6b.781|accessdate=13 June 2012|newspaper=[[Agence France-Presse]]|date=12 June 2012}}</ref> It is for the same reason that [[Tijuana]] and [[Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez]] are so valuable for the drug trafficking organizations.<ref name=longmirecartel/>\n\n==Past incidents in Nuevo Laredo==\n\n===2003 shootout===\nAt around 3&nbsp;am on 1 August 2003, the [[Federal Investigations Agency]] (AFI) confronted a group of armed men in the streets of [[Nuevo Laredo]]. Members of the AFI were staying at a hotel when Juan Manuel Mu\u00f1oz Morales, the attorney general of the city, called for help.<ref name=1abalacera>{{cite news|last=Gonz\u00e1lez |first=Iv\u00e1n |title=Todo sobre el enfrentamiento en Nuevo Laredo |url=http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/305538.html |accessdate=12 May 2012 |newspaper=[[Esmas.com]] |date=1 August 2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123173817/http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/305538.html |archivedate=23 November 2011 |language=es}}</ref> He was reportedly being chased by several individuals in a dark-colored truck. Consequently, the AFI officers followed the truck with seven of their vehicles, triggering a shootout between the police officers and alleged [[drug traffickers]].<ref name=1abalacera/> The armed confrontation lasted for more than 40 minutes, provoking \"panic\" and turning Nuevo Laredo into a \"battlefield.\"<ref name=nvolaredo03>{{cite news|last=Pruneda |first=Salvador |title=Balacera en Nuevo Laredo |url=http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/305170.html |accessdate=12 May 2012 |newspaper=[[Esmas.com]] |date=1 August 2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403060349/http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/305170.html |archivedate=3 April 2010 |language=es}}</ref> The gun detonations were heard throughout most of the city.<ref name=nvolaredo03/> Some witnesses, who preferred to remain anonymous, claimed that they saw over \"18 armed men in black with ski-masks.\"<ref name=nvolaredo03/>\n\nDuring the chase, five armed men in another vehicle shot at the police [[convoy]]. The triggermen in the two vehicles then engaged in a gunfight with the AFI for minutes, but one of the vehicles collided with a police truck. The vehicle the drug traffickers were in then caught on fire, and two of the gunmen were burned to death.<ref name=1abalacera/> The third one died on the sidewalk. According to [[Attorney General of Mexico|PGR]], the three gunmen that were killed were members of [[Los Negros]], a group of hitmen under the tutelage of [[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]] (a.k.a. ''El Chapo'') and of the [[Ju\u00e1rez Cartel]].<ref name=1abalacera/> Rocket-launchers, along with an \"inexact number of assault rifles,\" were reportedly used in the attack.<ref name=nvolaredo03/> In addition, the government agency stated that 198 municipal police officers were to be investigated for possible connections with the [[Gulf Cartel]]; Manuel Mu\u00f1oz, the attorney general who was being chased, was detained by the Mexican authorities. It is believed that he had liberated five members of [[Los Zetas]] who had been detained during the armed confrontation.<ref name=1abalacera/> According to [[Esmas.com]], this shooting was the first major gunfire in Nuevo Laredo between the Mexican authorities and cartel members in over thirty years.<ref>{{cite news|last=L\u00f3pez |first=Primitivo |title=Balacera entre narcos y agentes de la AFI |url=http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/304951.html |accessdate=12 May 2012 |newspaper=[[Esmas.com]] |date=1 August 2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123175140/http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/304951.html |archivedate=23 November 2011 |language=es}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1 January and 1 August 2003, 45 homicides were reported in Nuevo Laredo, along with 40 kidnappings.<ref name=nvolaredo03/>\n\n===''El Chapo'' enters Nuevo Laredo===\n[[File:El Chapo-Guzman.jpg|right|200px|thumb|Mug shot of [[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]], ''El Chapo''.]]\nAfter the apprehension of [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] in 2003, the former leader of the [[Gulf Cartel]], his criminal organization went through a leadership crisis, since there was no visible leader to take the lead of the cartel.<ref name=ravelo>{{cite book|last=Ravelo|first=Ricardo|title=El narco en M\u00e9xico|year=2011|publisher=Random House Mondadori|isbn=6073105649|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HAzOTSn5bSYC&pg=PT148&dq=nuevo+laredo+narco&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FPuuT83ZIYi22gWSkPnpCA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=nuevo%20laredo%20narco&f=false|language=es}}</ref> Nonetheless, [[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]], the drug boss of the Sinaloa cartel who is best known as ''El Chapo'', \"broke the rules\" and penetrated into [[Tamaulipas]]. His organization began to kill police officers\u2014forcing many to take a side with or against him\u2014and assassinating rival cartel members. The [[Mexican Armed Forces]] and the program ''M\u00e9xico Seguro'' were unable to put down the violence. For the first time in many years, the Mexican State was limited in its actions\u2014and even surpassed\u2014by the criminal organizations.<ref name=ravelo/> The [[Sinaloa Cartel]] stood to its firm intention to become the \"hegemonic drug trafficking organization in Mexico.\"<ref name=anabel>{{cite book|last=Hern\u00e1ndez|first=Anabel|title=Los se\u00f1ores del narco|year=2012|publisher=Random House Mondadori|isbn=6073108486|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oVLXjMuUrTgC&pg=PP373&dq=nuevo+laredo+narco&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FPuuT83ZIYi22gWSkPnpCA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=nuevo%20laredo%20narco&f=false|language=es}}</ref> And to do so, it had to control the cities along the U.S.-Mexico border. Back in the early 2000s, if a different drug trafficking organization wanted to traffic narcotics through a different corridor, they had to pay a fee to the cartel that controlled it. Hence, it often resulted in a high prize, since [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] \"knew how much every millimeter in his turf cost.\"<ref name=anabel/>\n\nNo drug trafficking organization before the Sinaloa cartel had dared to take on the [[Gulf Cartel]]. But [[Juan Jos\u00e9 Esparragoza Moreno]] and ''El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n'' were persuasive in moving on into Nuevo Laredo and the rest of Tamaulipas.<ref name=anabel/> One of the first steps in the war between the Gulf and Sinaloa cartels began when [[Arturo Beltr\u00e1n Leyva]], alias ''El Barbas'', hired Dionisio Rom\u00e1n Garc\u00eda (''El Chacho''), the leader of a gang who operated in [[Nuevo Laredo]] under the permission of Osiel in 2002. Nevertheless, ''El Chacho'' turned against the Osiel and the Gulf organization by deciding to work for the Sinaloa cartel and killing a Zeta member. This triggered a series of attacks and executions in [[Tamaulipas]].<ref name=anabel/> And, in order to put down the violence, ''El Barbas'' sought [[Arturo Guzm\u00e1n Decena]], one of the founders of Los Zetas, and told him that he \"did not want any problems\" with the [[Los Zetas|Zetas]], and that he would do his best to turn in ''El Chacho''. Guzm\u00e1n Decena accepted his apology, but told him that if anyone from the Sinaloa cartel wanted to traffic drugs inside the Gulf Cartel's territory, they had to be unarmed and under supervision.<ref name=anabel/>\n\nIn May 2002, ''El Chacho'' was kidnapped in the city of [[Monterrey]] by members of Los Zetas, and eventually found dead in Tamaulipas, bearing signs of torture.<ref name=ravelo/><ref>{{cite news|title=Identifican a ejecutados en Nuevo Le\u00f3n|url=http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/26270.html|accessdate=13 May 2012|newspaper=El Siglo de Torreon|date=4 April 2003|language=es}}</ref> ''El Barbas'' then asked Osiel if [[Edgar Valdez Villarreal]] (''La Barbie'') could replace ''El Chacho'', and he accepted. [[Los Zetas]], however, were not convinced nor happy with Osiel's decision, because for them, \"a betrayal is a betrayal.\"<ref name=anabel/> Fifteen days after the capture of Osiel, Valdez Villarreal called [[Heriberto Lazcano Lazcano]] (who had taken the lead of Los Zetas after the death of Guzm\u00e1n Decena in 2002) and said: \"You have a week to leave the territories from [[Reynosa]] to [[Nuevo Laredo]].\" With this, the war had started.<ref name=anabel/>\n\n==2012 incursions==\n{{Main|2011\u20132012 in the Mexican Drug War|Mexican Drug War}}\n\n===17 April 2012 massacre===\nDismembered remains of 14 men were found in several plastic bags inside a [[Chrysler Voyager#Generation III|Chrysler Voyager]] in the border city of [[Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas|Nuevo Laredo]], [[Tamaulipas]] on 17 April 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico authorities say bodies of 14 men dumped in Nuevo Laredo|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/world_now/2012/04/bodies-of-14-men-dumped-in-mexican-border-city.html|accessdate=18 April 2012|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=17 April 2012}}</ref> All of those killed were between the ages of 30 and 35.<ref>{{cite news|title=Localizan 14 cad\u00e1veres dentro de veh\u00edculo abandonado en Nuevo Laredo |url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/667913268f5737dec48f486e722aaf30 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120904062639/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/667913268f5737dec48f486e722aaf30 |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 September 2012 |accessdate=18 April 2012 |newspaper=[[Milenio]] |date=17 April 2012 |language=es}}</ref> Mexican officials stated that they found a \"messaged signed by a criminal group,\" but they did not release the content of the note,<ref>{{cite news|title=14 mutilated bodies found in Mexican border city |url=http://www.elpasotimes.com/juarez/ci_20419518/14-mutilated-bodies-found-mexican-border-city |accessdate=18 April 2012 |newspaper=[[El Paso Times]] |date=17 April 2012 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> nor if those killed were members of Los Zetas or of the [[Gulf Cartel]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Mosso |first=Rub\u00e9n |title=Nuevo Laredo: hallan 14 cuerpos mutilados |url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/667913268f5737dec48f486e725f91a7 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130104011548/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/667913268f5737dec48f486e725f91a7 |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 January 2013 |accessdate=18 April 2012 |newspaper=[[Milenio]] |date=18 April 2012 |language=es}}</ref> ''[[CNN en Espa\u00f1ol|CNNM\u00e9xico]]'' stated that the message left behind by the criminal group said that they were going to \"clean up Nuevo Laredo\" by killing Zeta members.<ref>{{cite news|title=14 cuerpos mutilados fueron hallados en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://blogs.cnnmexico.com/ultimas-noticias/2012/04/17/14-cuerpos-mutilados-fueron-hallados-en-nuevo-laredo/|accessdate=18 April 2012|newspaper=[[CNN en Espa\u00f1ol|CNNM\u00e9xico]]|date=17 April 2012|language=es}}</ref> ''[[The Monitor (Texas)|The Monitor]]'' newspaper, however, said that a source outside law enforcement but with direct knowledge of the attacks stated the 14 bodies belonged to members of [[Los Zetas]] who had been killed by the [[Jalisco New Generation Cartel]], now a branch of the [[Sinaloa Cartel]].<ref>{{cite news|title=14 bodies found in minivan outside Nuevo Laredo City Hall, according to Tamps. gov't |url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/bodies-60209-hall-city.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427034103/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/bodies-60209-hall-city.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 April 2012 |accessdate=18 April 2012 |newspaper=[[The Monitor (Texas)|The Monitor]] |date=17 April 2012 }}</ref> Following the attacks, the Sinaloa cartel's kingpin, [[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]]\u2014better known as ''El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n''\u2014sent a message to [[Los Zetas]] that they will fight for the control of the Nuevo Laredo plaza.<ref>{{cite news|title=El Chapo demuestra su poder en Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas |url=http://www.blogdelnarco.com/2012/04/el-chapo-demuestra-su-poder-en-nuevo-laredo-tamps/ |accessdate=18 April 2012 |newspaper=[[Blog del Narco]] |date=18 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120420210702/http://www.blogdelnarco.com/2012/04/el-chapo-demuestra-su-poder-en-nuevo-laredo-tamps/ |archivedate=20 April 2012 |language=es}}</ref> The message read the following:\n{{Quotation|\"We have begun to clear Nuevo Laredo of Zetas because we want a free city and so you can live in peace. We are narcotics traffickers and we don't mess with honest working or business people. I'm going to teach these scums to work Sinaloa style\u2014without kidnapping, without payoffs, without extortion. As for you, 40, I tell you that you don't scare me. I know you sent H to toss heads here in my turf, because you don't have the stones nor the people to do it yourself. Don't forget that I'm your true father.\"| [[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]], <small>(El Chapo)</small><ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Dane|title=Drug lord \"El Chapo\" declares war on Zetas|url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Drug-lord-El-Chapo-declares-war-on-Zetas-3492866.php|accessdate=19 April 2012|newspaper=[[The Houston Chronicle]]|date=18 April 2012}}</ref>}}\n\n[[Nuevo Laredo]] is considered a stronghold of Los Zetas,<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexican authorities find 14 dead in Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2012/04/mexican-authorities-find-14-dead-in.html|accessdate=18 April 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=17 April 2012}}</ref> although there were incursions by the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] in March 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n comienza limpia de Los Zetas en Tamaulipas|url=http://www.blogdelnarco.com/2012/03/el-chapo-guzman-comienza-limpia-de-los-zetas-en-tamaulipas/|accessdate=18 April 2012|newspaper=[[Blog del Narco]]|date=26 March 2012|language=es}}</ref><ref name=insightnuevolaredo1>{{cite news|last=Corcoran |first=Patrick |title='Narcomantas' Herald Chapo's Incursion into Mexico Border State |url=http://insightcrime.org/insight-latest-news/item/2414-narcomantas-herald-chapos-incursion-into-mexico-border-state |accessdate=18 April 2012 |newspaper=[[InSight Crime]] |date=28 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120409054719/http://insightcrime.org/insight-latest-news/item/2414-narcomantas-herald-chapos-incursion-into-mexico-border-state |archivedate=9 April 2012 }}</ref> Consequently, Los Zetas responded two days later with incursions to [[Sinaloa]], the home state of the Sinaloa Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|last=Martinez|first=Chivis|title=Z40 Answers Chapo by Leaving His Own Butchery and Message|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2012/03/z40-answers-chapo-by-leaving-his-own.html|accessdate=19 April 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=28 March 2012}}</ref> The Sinaloa Cartel's first attempt to take over Nuevo Laredo happened in 2005, when [[Los Zetas]] was working as the armed wing of the [[Gulf Cartel]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Dane|title=Is 'El Chapo' back in border city of Nuevo Laredo?|url=http://blog.chron.com/narcoconfidential/2012/04/with-butchery-and-a-warning-is-mexicos-el-chapo-back-in-border-city-of-nuevo-laredo/|accessdate=19 April 2012|newspaper=[[The Houston Chronicle]]|date=18 April 2012}}</ref>\n;InSight Crime analysis\n[[File:NuevoLaredo-narcokillings.jpg|left|180px|thumb|Front page of the killings in [[Nuevo Laredo]].]]\nThe \"40\" in the message is a reference to [[Miguel Trevi\u00f1o Morales]], a top leader of Los Zetas based in Nuevo Laredo, and longtime adversary of ''El Chapo'' Guzm\u00e1n. The \"H\" is presumably [[H\u00e9ctor Beltr\u00e1n Leyva]], the last remaining brother of the [[Beltr\u00e1n Leyva Cartel]].<ref name=insightanalysis>{{cite news|last=Corcoran|first=Patrick|title=Bodies, Banner Herald Sinaloa Cartel's Push East|url=http://insightcrime.org/insight-latest-news/item/2529-more-evidence-of-chapos-arrival-in-mexico-border-town|accessdate=24 April 2012|newspaper=[[InSight Crime]]|date=23 April 2012}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The Beltr\u00e1n Leyva organization, unlike the Zetas, has presence in Sinaloa state, and would probably have an easier time attacking the Sinaloa Cartel on its own turf. The message does not mention the fact that the [[Gulf Cartel]] is probably supporting the Sinaloa Cartel in carrying out the executions.<ref name=insightanalysis/> In addition, the banner suggests that the alliance between Los Zetas and the Beltr\u00e1n Leyva Cartel remains intact as of 2012 despite its losses it lived in 2008. The message also suggests the differences in the modus operandi of [[Los Zetas]] and the [[Sinaloa Cartel]], because as authors of InSight Crime allege, the Zetas have a reputation of operating through extortions, kidnappings, robberies, and other illicit activities; in contrast, the Sinaloa Cartel is known simply for drug trafficking. (Both assertions are not wholly true, but often reflect a popular sentiment). Guzm\u00e1n attempted to take over Nuevo Laredo after the capture of the Gulf Cartel leader, [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], in 2003.<ref name=insightanalysis/>\n\nNevertheless, Guzm\u00e1n retreated after a few years of bloody turf wars. The Sinaloa Cartel's return to Nuevo Laredo, however, was seen again in March 2012 after Guzm\u00e1n reportedly left several corpses and a message heralding his return.<ref name=insightnuevolaredo1/> According to the [[Bureau of Transportation Statistics]], Nuevo Laredo is the busiest border crossing in terms of truck crossings with over 1.7 million trucks a year, more than double than any other crossing in the Mexico\u2013United States border.<ref name=bts>{{cite web|title=Border Crossing/Entry Data: Quick Search by Rankings|url=http://www.bts.gov/programs/international/transborder/TBDR_BC/TBDR_BC_QuickSearch.html|publisher=[[Bureau of Transportation Statistics]]|accessdate=24 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702013155/http://www.bts.gov/programs/international/transborder/TBDR_BC/TBDR_BC_QuickSearch.html|archive-date=2 July 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Nuevo Laredo is the fourth-busiest border crossing in terms of passenger vehicles.<ref name=bts/> Patrick Corcoran of InSight Crime believes that the turf war in Nuevo Laredo will bring a huge wave of violence, but also mentioned that the circumstances have changed since the split of the [[Gulf Cartel]] and [[Los Zetas]] in early 2010. The current alliance between Guzm\u00e1n's Sinaloa Cartel and the Gulf Cartel may successfully extract Los Zetas and give ''El Chapo'' the upper hand.\n\nAnd once the Sinaloa Cartel gets established in Nuevo Laredo, it may possibly make moves to control [[Reynosa]] and [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]].<ref name=insightanalysis/>\n\n;Investigations\nOn 24 April 2012, the attorney general of the state of [[Tamaulipas]] identified 10 of the 14 people killed. In addition, the Mexican authorities stated that those killed had \"no relationship with the criminal group [[Los Zetas]],\" and that they were in fact innocent civilians.<ref name=lapoliciacainnocentes>{{cite news|title=Desligan al \"Chapo Guzman\" de la masacre en Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas|url=http://www.lapoliciaca.com/nota-roja/desligan-al-chapo-guzman-de-la-masacre-en-nuevo-laredo-tamaulipas/|accessdate=26 April 2012|newspaper=La Policiaca|date=24 April 2012|language=es}}</ref> The [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] indicated that 7 out of the 14 who were killed were reportedly deported immigrants who were working illegally in the United States.<ref name=lapoliciacainnocentes/> The authorities said that the massacre was carried out to generate \"psychosis,\" because there is no concrete evidence of a \"war between drug cartels\" nor elements that indicate the presence of a group representing the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] in the border city of Nuevo Laredo.<ref>{{cite news|title=Desligan a Chapo de masacre de N. Laredo|url=http://noticias.terra.com.mx/mexico/estados/desligan-a-chapo-de-masacre-de-n-laredo,41a982f1b07e6310VgnVCM10000098cceb0aRCRD.html|accessdate=26 April 2012|newspaper=[[Terra Networks]]|date=24 April 2012|language=es}}</ref><ref name=guerraentrecarteles/> Some of the bodies have been returned to their families.<ref>{{cite news|last=Guzm\u00e1n|first=Julio Manuel|title=Identifican a 7 de 14 asesinados en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/843349.html|accessdate=26 April 2012|newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|date=24 April 2012|language=es}}</ref> The rest of the corpses have not been identified and remain in the Forensic Medical Services (SEMEFO).<ref name=guerraentrecarteles>{{cite news|title=Identifican a 7 de los 14 asesinados en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.noticiasdetamaulipas.com/nota.cgi?id=410791|accessdate=27 April 2012|newspaper=Noticias de Tamaulipas|date=24 April 2012|language=es}}</ref>\n\n===4 May 2012 massacre===\n23 bodies\u201414 of them decapitated and 9 of them hanged from a bridge\u2014were discovered in [[Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas]], in an escalation of brutal violence involving rival drug gangs on the U.S. border.<ref name=nuevecolgados/> In the first incident, at around 1:00&nbsp;am on 4 May 2012, nine people were hanged from a bridge on the [[Mexican Federal Highway 85D]] with a message left behind by the killers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Los cuerpos de 23 personas son encontrados en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2012/05/04/los-cuerpos-de-23-personas-son-encontrados-en-nuevo-laredo|accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=CNNM\u00e9xico|date=4 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> Horrified motorists encountered the blood-stained bodies of four women and five men hanging off a bridge.<ref name=golfas/><ref>{{cite news|title=23 dead in day of horror for Mexico border city|url=http://au.news.yahoo.com/world/a/-/world/13608544/23-dead-in-day-of-horror-for-mexico-border-city/|accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=[[Yahoo! News]]|date=4 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120516195543/http://au.news.yahoo.com/world/a/-/world/13608544/23-dead-in-day-of-horror-for-mexico-border-city/|archive-date=16 May 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The banner left behind reportedly stated that those killed were the perpetrators of the car bomb in the city on 24 April 2012.<ref name=nuevecolgados>{{cite news|title=Nuevo Laredo vive un viernes negro, jornada violenta deja 23 muertos|url=http://excelsior.com.mx/index.php?m=nota&seccion=seccion-nacional&cat=1&id_nota=831656|accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]|date=4 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> In addition, the 9 people who were hanged on the bridge were reportedly members of the [[Gulf Cartel]] who were killed by [[Los Zetas]] for \"heating up\" their turf.<ref>{{cite news|title=Suman 23 muertos en Nuevo Laredo, entre colgados y decapitados|url=http://noticias.univision.com/narcotrafico/noticias/article/2012-05-04/nueve-cuerpos-colgados-puente-nuevo-laredo-mexico-narco-zetas#axzz1tvkHuxlD|accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=[[Univision]]|date=4 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> The message read the following:\n{{Quotation|\"Fucking ([[Gulf Cartel]]) whores, this is how I'm going to finish off every fucker you send to heat up the turf. You have to fuck up sometime and that's when I'm gonna put you in your place. We are going to fuck up ''El Gringo'' that keeps setting off [[car bombs]]; the fucker Juanito Carrizales and his friend ''El Tubi'', who I killed because he kept crying like a bitch; ''El Metro 4'' who asked Comandante [[Heriberto Lazcano Lazcano|Lazcano]] for mercy when he was kicking the shit out of him; and now ''[[Juan Mej\u00eda Gonz\u00e1lez|El R1]]'' in [[Reynosa]] and you. But it's okay, here are your guys. The rest went away but I'll get them. Sooner or later. See you around fuckers.<ref name=golfas>{{cite news|title=Ejecutan y cuelgan a nueve personas en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.blogdelnarco.com/2012/05/ejecutan-y-cuelgan-a-nueve-personas-en-nuevo-laredo/|accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=[[Blog del Narco]]|date=4 May 2012|language=es}}</ref>| [[Los Zetas]]}}\n\nIn the second incident, which occurred hours later, 14 decapitated bodies were abandoned inside a vehicle in front of the Customs Agency;<ref name=universal23/> the severed heads were left inside several ice coolers in front of the municipal palace.<ref name=universal23>{{cite news|title=Van 23 muertos en Nuevo Laredo, en ola de violencia|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/845350.html|accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|date=4 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> The Mexican police said the second massacre could have been an act of revenge by the [[Gulf Cartel]] to Los Zetas for the earlier killings.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bodies of 23 found dumped near U.S. border in Mexico drug war|url=https://news.yahoo.com/nine-bodies-hung-bridge-northern-mexico-174942376.html|accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=[[Yahoo! News]]|date=4 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Se recrudece violencia en Nuevo Laredo: 23 muertos|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/estados/85705.html|accessdate=5 May 2012|newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|date=5 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> Along with the decapitated bodies was a message allegedly signed by [[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]], where he demanded the municipality mayor of [[Nuevo Laredo]], Benjam\u00edn Galv\u00e1n, along with other municipal and state leaders and public safety officials to recognize the Sinaloa cartel's presence in the area and stop insisting he is not in the city.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pide \"El Chapo Guzman\" al alcalde de Nuevo Laredo que deje de negar su presencia|url=http://www.lapoliciaca.com/nota-roja/pide-el-chapo-guzman-al-alcalde-de-nuevo-laredo-que-deje-de-negar-su-presencia/|accessdate=6 May 2012|newspaper=La Policiaca|date=6 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> The message read the following:\n{{Quotation|\"You want credibility that I am in [[Nuevo Laredo|NL]]?  What will it take, bringing the heads of [[Los Zetas|Zeta]] leaders?  Or yours? Mr. [Benjam\u00edn Galv\u00e1n], since you want to give us a sweet treat, with you coming out saying that nothing is happening here and all is well, continue with the same and I assure you that heads will keep rolling. Keep making [[Miguel Trevi\u00f1o Morales|Z-40]]'s case to say and deny that we already operate in [[Nuevo Laredo]], just so that [[Heriberto Lazcano Lazcano|Lazcano]] will not scold this illiterate car washer. And you [Alfonso Olvera], Director of Public Security appointed entirely by Z-40, who is your buddy, keep declaring that my staff does not operate here in Nuevo Laredo. Or you, [V\u00edctor Almanza], stating that the dismembered were masons, traders, migrants or simple and humble workers (and not what they were [[Los Zetas|Zetas]]). Continue to deny my presence here in [[Nuevo Laredo]] and you will continue to see their heads. I do not kill innocent people to submit work as you are accustomed [[Miguel Trevi\u00f1o Morales|Z-40]], all dead in Nuevo Laredo are pure scums, in other words, pure [[Los Zetas|Z]]. Sincerely, your father.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Chapo Leaves Message with Decapitated Bodies Issues Threat against NL Mayor|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2012/05/chapo-leaves-message-with-decapitated.html|accessdate=6 May 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=6 May 2012}}</ref>|[[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]], <small>(El Chapo)</small>}}\n\n==Car bomb attacks==\nAt around 8:00&nbsp;a.m. on 24 April 2012 in [[Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas]], a car bomb exploded outside the city's police department.<ref>{{cite news|title=Car bomb explosion followed by shootout in Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?id=745672#.T5eVxcS3CFc|accessdate=25 April 2012|newspaper=[[KGBT-TV]]|date=24 April 2012}}</ref> When the Mexican military arrived at the area of the explosion, they engaged in a confrontation with cartel members who shot them upon their arrival.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coche bomba y enfrentamiento en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/843249.html|accessdate=25 April 2012|newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|date=24 April 2012|language=es}}</ref> There was one civilian who was injured as a result of the car bomb.<ref>{{cite news|title=Confirman coche-bomba en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://noticias.terra.com.mx/mexico/seguridad/confirman-coche-bomba-en-nuevo-laredo,7cc0b7efda6e6310VgnVCM5000009ccceb0aRCRD.html|accessdate=25 April 2012|newspaper=[[Terra Networks]]|date=24 April 2012|language=es}}</ref> The ''[[Blog del Narco]]'' credited the attacks to [[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]] (a.k.a. ''El Chapo''), who reportedly left another message for [[Los Zetas]] about the Sinaloa cartel's incursion in Nuevo Laredo.<ref>{{cite news|title=Reafirma El Chapo presencia en Tamaulipas con coche bomba|url=http://www.blogdelnarco.com/2012/04/reafirma-el-chapo-presencia-en-tamulipas-con-coche-bomba/|accessdate=25 April 2012|newspaper=[[Blog del Narco]]|date=24 April 2012|language=es}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cochebomba-Nuevo Laredo.jpeg|right|260px|thumb|[[Car bomb]] explosion outside the city hall in Nuevo Laredo.]]\nIn the second incident, suspected members of a drug trafficking organization opened fire at a hotel that the [[Federal Police (Mexico)|Federal police]] was using as barracks on 23 May 2012, and then set off a car bomb in front of the police dormitories.<ref>{{cite news|title=Photos of damage from hotel car bombing in Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?id=758095#.T8AdJHlYvDE|accessdate=26 May 2012|newspaper=[[KGBT-TV]]|date=24 May 2012}}</ref><ref name=zetasbomb/> A Chevrolet pickup truck exploded at around 5:30&nbsp;a.m. inside the parking lot of Hotel Santa Cecilia in southern Nuevo Laredo, injuring 2 civilians and 8 police officers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Estalla coche bomba en Nuevo Laredo; 8 polic\u00edas y 2 civiles resultaron heridos|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2012/05/25/index.php?section=politica&article=016n1pol&partner=rss|accessdate=25 May 2012|newspaper=[[La Jornada]]|date=25 May 2012|language=es}}</ref><ref name=valenciabomb>{{cite news|last=Valencia|first=Nick|title=Gun and bomb attack on hotel in Mexican border town wounds 10|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/05/25/world/americas/mexico-violence/|accessdate=25 May 2012|newspaper=[[CNN International]]|date=25 May 2012}}</ref> The blast was strong enough to partially damage several rooms in the hotel and a couple of vehicles.<ref name=valenciabomb/><ref>{{cite news|title=Estalla coche bomba en Nuevo Laredo; al menos 10 heridos|url=http://excelsior.com.mx/index.php?m=nota&seccion=seccion-nacional&cat=1&id_nota=836523|accessdate=25 May 2012|newspaper=[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]|date=24 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> Three of the ten police officers were wounded with third degree burns in half of their bodies, while the rest were treated for non-life-threatening wounds.<ref name=valenciabomb/> Many residents living in Nuevo Laredo and across the international border in [[Laredo, Texas]] were reportedly awaken by the car explosion.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bomb in Mexico felt in Texas|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/article/Bomb-in-Mexico-felt-in-Texas-3584541.php|accessdate=25 May 2012|newspaper=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|date=24 May 2012}}</ref> Some Laredo residents also began calling [[9-1-1]] early in the morning as the cartel battles in Nuevo Laredo reached their peak.<ref name=shook/> One resident even said that the explosions in Nuevo Laredo made his house shake across the border.<ref name=shook>{{cite news|title=Laredo Residents Wake Up To Sounds of Explosions, Gunfire|url=http://www.pro8news.com/news/local/Laredo-Residents-Wake-Up-To-Sounds-of-Explosions-Gunfire-153803235.html|accessdate=25 May 2012|newspaper=[[KGNS-TV]]|date=24 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528114917/http://www.pro8news.com/news/local/Laredo-Residents-Wake-Up-To-Sounds-of-Explosions-Gunfire-153803235.html|archive-date=28 May 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Soon after the attacks, the [[Mexican Army]] put up a military checkpoint in the avenue where the hotel is situated.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coche bomba explota en hotel en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://eleconomista.com.mx/seguridad-publica/2012/05/24/coche-bomba-explota-hotel-nuevo-laredo|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[El Economista (Mexico)|El Economista]]|date=24 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> In addition, this attack was the first attack directed to Tamaulipas' new state police force, which took over the duties of the municipal police forces that were considered ineffective and corrupt.<ref>{{cite news|last=Weissenstein|first=Michael|title=Mexico Gang Launches Car Bomb Near US Border|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/mexico-gang-launches-car-bomb-us-border-16426137#.T7_IV3lYvDE|accessdate=25 May 2012|newspaper=[[ABC News]]|date=24 May 2012}}</ref> The authorities in the Mexican state of Tamaulipas believe that [[Los Zetas]], one of Mexico's most powerful criminal groups, carried out the attack. Los Zetas are known for carrying out a number of attacks, but this one was described as \"one of the most elaborate.\"<ref name=zetasbomb>{{cite news|title=Mexico gang launches car bomb near US border|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5jFT8jVncDy-KLN8GVOVBDsm86LNg?docId=771194735b844dc19c892c1153c89dd8|accessdate=25 May 2012|newspaper=[[Associated Press]]|date=25 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nA third car bomb was abandoned on 29 June 2012 in front of the municipal palace at around 11:00&nbsp;a.m., and exploded just below the office of Benjam\u00edn Galv\u00e1n G\u00f3mez, the mayor of Nuevo Laredo.<ref name=ventana>{{cite news|title=Estallan auto frente a Palacio en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/856428.html|accessdate=29 June 2012|newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|date=29 June 2012|language=es}}</ref> Explosives were planted inside a gray [[Ford Ranger]] pickup truck, damaging more than ten vehicles that were parked near the car bomb and destroying dozens of windows in its surroundings.<ref name=ventana/><ref name=salaredo>{{cite news|last=Buch|first=Jason|title=Car bomb rocks Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/local_news/article/Car-bomb-rocks-Nuevo-Laredo-3673813.php|accessdate=29 June 2012|newspaper=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|date=29 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=H\u00e9ctor|title=Coche bomba estalla frente a alcald\u00eda de Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/index.php?m=nota&seccion=seccion-nacional&cat=28&id_nota=844445&rss=1|accessdate=29 June 2012|newspaper=[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]|date=29 June 2012}}</ref> The detonation was heard on both sides of the U.S.-Mexico border.<ref>{{cite news|title=Possible Car Bomb at Nuevo Laredo City Hall|url=http://www.pro8news.com/news/local/Possible-Car-Bomb-at-Nuevo-Laredo-City-Hall-160854945.html|accessdate=29 June 2012|newspaper=[[KGNS-TV]]|date=29 June 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130131232937/http://www.pro8news.com/news/local/Possible-Car-Bomb-at-Nuevo-Laredo-City-Hall-160854945.html|archive-date=31 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Laredo police said they received calls from several residents reporting an explosion, and dispatched officiers to the [[international bridges in Laredo, Texas|international bridges]] in the Texan city. A plume of smoke was seen from the U.S. side too.<ref name=salaredo/> In addition, seven people who were near the explosion were injured.<ref name=expression>{{cite news|title=Siete lesionados por granadazo: Gobierno de Tamaulipas|url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/dbd1ce87b7901fd6e2aa1bc5f7e32f42|accessdate=29 June 2012|newspaper=[[Milenio]]|date=29 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120701154141/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/dbd1ce87b7901fd6e2aa1bc5f7e32f42|archive-date=1 July 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all|language=es}}</ref> The Federal police and the Mexican Army cordoned the crime scene, as paramedics stabilized the bystanders and transported them to the nearest hospital.<ref>{{cite news|title=Car bomb wounds 7 in Mexican border city|url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/news/2012/06/29/car-bomb-wounds-7-in-mexican-border-city/|accessdate=29 June 2012|newspaper=[[Fox News]]|date=29 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304063149/http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/news/2012/06/29/car-bomb-wounds-7-in-mexican-border-city/|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Mexican authorities believe this car bomb attack was a form of \"expression\" by the criminal syndicates who operate in Nuevo Laredo and want to make their presence known.<ref name=expression/> The state of Tamaulipas pledged to intensify the security measures in Nuevo Laredo.<ref>{{cite news|title=Un coche bomba explota frente al edificio municipal de Nuevo Laredo|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2012/06/29/un-coche-bomba-explota-frente-al-edificio-municipal-de-nuevo-laredo|accessdate=29 June 2012|newspaper=CNNM\u00e9xico|date=29 June 2012|language=es}}</ref>\n\n==Attacks against the media==\n{{See also|List of journalists killed in the Mexican Drug War}}\nOn 19 March 2004, journalist [[Roberto Javier Mora Garc\u00eda]] was stabbed 26 times outside his home in Nuevo Laredo.<ref>{{cite web|title=El asesinato de Roberto Mora Garc\u00eda, director editorial de \"El Ma\u00f1ana\", lleva cinco a\u00f1os impune|url=http://www.ifex.org/mexico/2009/03/24/murder_of_newspaper_director_robert/es/|publisher=[[International Freedom of Expression Exchange]]|accessdate=12 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> On 6 February 2006, two armed men broke into the offices of ''El Ma\u00f1ana'' and detonated a grenade.<ref name=terra2006>{{cite news|title=Diario \"El Ma\u00f1ana\" de Nuevo Laredo sufre atentado|url=http://noticias.terra.com.mx/mexico/seguridad/diario-el-manana-de-nuevo-laredo-sufre-atentado,34eb1273c1147310VgnVCM4000009bcceb0aRCRD.html|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[Terra Networks]]|date=12 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> They also shot the outside walls of the installation with [[AK-47]]s and [[AR-15]]s before fleeing the scene.<ref name=terra2006/> According to ''[[La Jornada]]'', the armed men shot the installation more than 100 times, injuring Jaime Orozco Tey, a journalist.<ref>{{cite news|title=Irrupci\u00f3n armada en el peri\u00f3dico El Ma\u00f1ana de Nuevo Laredo; un herido|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2006/02/07/index.php?section=politica&article=022n1pol|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[La Jornada]]|date=6 February 2006|language=es}}</ref> On 30 July 2010, a group of armed men in a vehicle threw a grenade at the offices of [[Televisa]] in Nuevo Laredo, damaging two vehicles.<ref>{{cite news|title=Atacan El Ma\u00f1ana de Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.elmanana.com/diario/noticia/tamaulipas/noticias/atacan_el_manana_de_nuevo_laredo/1620047|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=El Ma\u00f1ana|date=12 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> On 26 September 2011, Mar\u00eda Elizabeth Mac\u00edas Castro, an editor of la ''Primera Hora'' newspaper, was decapitated; a note was left behind by Los Zetas, claiming responsibility for the killing.<ref>{{cite news|last=Chapa|first=Sergio|title=Journalist group condemns Nuevo Laredo editor's murder|url=http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?id=667650#.T66yHZ9YvDE|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[KGBT-TV]]|date=29 September 2011}}</ref> The message read the following: \"For those who don't want to believe, this happened to [Mar\u00eda Elizabeth Mac\u00edas Castro] because of [her] actions, for believing in the army and the navy. Thank you for your attention, respectfully, [[Los Zetas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Another social media killing in Nuevo Laredo|url=http://blog.mysanantonio.com/beyondtheborder/2011/09/another-social-media-killing-in-nuevo-laredo/|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|date=27 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Attacks against bloggers and social media users===\nOn 13 September 2011, a man and a woman in their early twenties were hanged from a pedestrian bridge in Nuevo Laredo.<ref name=septembertwit>{{cite news|last=Castillo |first=Mariano |title=Bodies hanging from bridge in Mexico are warning to social media users |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2011-09-14/world/mexico.violence_1_zetas-cartel-social-media-users-nuevo-laredo?_s=PM:WORLD |accessdate=12 May 2012 |publisher=CNN |date=14 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510001812/http://articles.cnn.com/2011-09-14/world/mexico.violence_1_zetas-cartel-social-media-users-nuevo-laredo?_s=PM%3AWORLD |archivedate=10 May 2012 }}</ref> Their fingers and ears were mutilated, and both bore signs of torture.<ref name=septembertwit/> The signs left behind declared that the pair were killed for posting denouncements of the drug cartel activities on the Internet.<ref name=balconear>{{cite news|title=Balconear a criminales en Internet firm\u00f3 su sentencia de muerte|url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/index.php?m=nota&seccion=&cat=&id_nota=768253|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]|date=14 September 2011|language=es}}</ref> The message read: \"This is going to happen to all of those posting funny things on the Internet,\" one sign said. \"You better (expletive) pay attention. I'm about to get you.\"<ref name=septembertwit/> The killing was carried out by [[Los Zetas]].<ref name=septembertwit/> \nOn 9 November 2011, a blogger was tortured and decapitated for allegedly denouncing against the organized crime groups online.<ref name=rascatripa/> The man killed reportedly used the username \"Rascatripa\" in the site known as ''Nuevo Laredo en Vivo'', where civilians post on the activities of [[Los Zetas]].<ref name=rascatripa>{{cite news|title=Decapitan a cibernauta; van cuatro en dos meses|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=287540|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]|date=9 November 2011|language=es}}</ref> The killers left another message on top of the corpse stating the following: \"Hello! I'm Rascatripas and this happened to me for failing to understand that I should not report things on social media websites. With this last report I bid farewell to Nuevo Laredo en Vivo.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Nuevo Laredo: Man tortured and decapitated for allegedly denouncing cartel activity online|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2011/11/nuevo-laredo-man-tortured-and.html|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=9 November 2011}}</ref> This man was the fourth killed by the cartels for posting against them on the Internet in less than two months.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fitch|first=Nubia|title=Asesinan a otro usuario de redes sociales|url=http://www.sexenio.com.mx/articulo.php?id=10644|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=Sexenio|date=9 November 2011|language=es}}</ref> The brutal killings sent \"shock waves\" to the online community, and Twitter users from [[Nuevo Laredo]], [[Reynosa]], and the [[Rio Grande Valley]], along with other border communities, issued a joint statement asking for protection in November 2011.<ref name=rgvcomplain>{{cite news|last=Sergio|first=Chapa|title=Twitter users want justice after fourth social media murder in Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?id=685186#.T67GwZ9YvDE|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[KGBT-TV]]|date=10 November 2011}}</ref> The bloggers asked the Mexican government to solve the murders and protect freedom of speech.<ref name=rgvcomplain/> Even the \"hacker group\" known as [[Anonymous (group)|Anonymous]] stepped in and gave recommendations to the community in Nuevo Laredo to \"be careful\" when denouncing Los Zetas.<ref>{{cite news|last=Althaus|first=Dudley|title=Gang sends message with blogger beheading|url=http://www.chron.com/news/nation-world/article/Gang-sends-message-with-blogger-beheading-2260814.php|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=11 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Cartels silence the media===\nIn another incident, a group of armed men attacked the offices of ''[[El Ma\u00f1ana (Nuevo Laredo)|El Ma\u00f1ana]]'' newspaper at around 23:00 hours on 11 May 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ataca comando a peri\u00f3dico en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/846811.html|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|date=12 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> The Mexican authorities stated that no one was injured in the 5-minute shootout, but the offices and some vehicles were damaged when bullets impacted from the outside.<ref>{{cite news|title=Armed men open fire on Mexican newspaper office in border city of Nuevo Laredo|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/armed-men-open-fire-on-mexican-newspaper-office-in-border-city-of-nuevo-laredo/2012/05/12/gIQApi3TJU_story.html|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|date=12 May 2012}}</ref> When the employees of ''El Ma\u00f1ana'' heard the detonations, they threw themselves on the floor, while others suffered nervous breakdowns.<ref>{{cite news|title=Comando ataca a balazos el peri\u00f3dico El Ma\u00f1ana de Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=307229|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]|date=12 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> Some witnesses mentioned that they heard grenade explosions during the attack. In addition, a message was reportedly left behind by the perpetrators.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ataca comando peri\u00f3dico 'El Ma\u00f1ana' de Nuevo Laredo; no hay heridos |url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2012/05/12/95952011-ataca-comando-periodico-el-manana-de-nuevo-laredo/ |accessdate=12 May 2012 |newspaper=[[La Jornada]] |date=12 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514023409/http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2012/05/12/95952011-ataca-comando-periodico-el-manana-de-nuevo-laredo |archivedate=14 May 2012 |df=dmy |language=es}}</ref>\n\nThe damage was minimal, but the message was understood. ''El Ma\u00f1ana'' took the attack as a warning from the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] that it wants coverage claiming that they are taking over Nuevo Laredo and beating Los Zetas, therefore making the Sinaloa cartel look \"tough\" and Los Zetas \"look weak.\"<ref name=sinaloazetasmanana>{{cite news|last=O'Conner|first=Mike|title=El Ma\u00f1ana cedes battle to report on Mexican violence|url=http://www.cpj.org/blog/2012/05/el-manana-cedes-battle-to-report-on-mexican-violen.php|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[Committee to Protect Journalists]]|date=23 May 2012}}</ref> The problem is that if the journalists decide to favor the Sinaloa cartel or Los Zetas, they will find themselves threatened by one of the cartels. In other words, one cartel threatens if there isn't coverage (Sinaloa cartel) and the other cartel threatens if there is coverage (Los Zetas).<ref name=sinaloazetasmanana/> Following the attacks, ''[[El Ma\u00f1ana (Nuevo Laredo)|El Ma\u00f1ana]]'' declared that it will no longer report on news relating to [[Mexican Drug War|drug-violence]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Turati|first=Marcela|title=Tras atentado, El Ma\u00f1ana dejar\u00e1 de publicar notas sobre narcoviolencia|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=307452|accessdate=15 May 2012|newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]|date=14 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> They may in fact be the first newspaper to publicly step down and stop covering all crime incidents involving stories of mafia groups fighting for control.<ref name=sinaloazetasmanana/> The day that the editorial stepped down, [[Cadereyta Jim\u00e9nez massacre|49 decapitated bodies]] were found along a highway near Monterrey, Mexico's third largest city, and just 120 miles south of Nuevo Laredo. Most newspapers covered this incident, but ''El Ma\u00f1ana'' did not.<ref name=sinaloazetasmanana/> Again, on 10 June 2012, ''El Ma\u00f1ana'' suffered another grenade attack but only material damages were reported.<ref>{{cite news|title=Three Mexican news outlets targeted in one day|url=http://www.cpj.org/2012/07/three-mexican-news-outlets-targeted-in-one-day.php|accessdate=11 July 2012|newspaper=[[Committee to Protect Journalists]]|date=11 July 2012}}</ref> In response to the attacks, the newspaper issued the following message to the public:\n{{Quotation|We ask for the public's comprehension and will [[Censorship|refrain]], for as long as needed, from publishing any information related to the [[Mexican Drug War|violent disputes]] our city and other regions of the country are suffering ... The company's editorial and administrative board has been forced to make this regrettable decision by circumstances we are all familiar with, and by the lack of adequate conditions for freely exercising professional [[journalism]] ... We will only address the (violent crime) issue through the [[Opinion journalism|opinions]] of professional analysts who study the phenomenon in an intelligent and responsible way ... [We will not] serve the petty interests of any de-facto power or criminal group.<ref>{{cite news|last=[[Ioan Grillo]]|title=Mexico paper stops drug war coverage after grenade attacks|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/07/11/us-mexico-drugs-newspaper-idUSBRE86A1IR20120711|accessdate=12 July 2012|newspaper=[[Reuters]]|date=11 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=El Manana Newspaper To Stop Covering Certain Stories After Second Grenade Attack|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/11/el-manana-newspaper-stories-grenade-attack_n_1664978.html|accessdate=11 July 2012|newspaper=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=11 July 2012}}</ref>}}\nMany Mexicans have been relying on social media chatrooms and sites like Facebook and Twitter as traditional media \"self-censor in the face of cartel violence.\"<ref name=msnblog>{{cite news|title=Blogger on Mexico cartel beheading: Cannot kill us all|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/45230870|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[MSN News]]|date=10 November 2011}}</ref> Moreover, due to the violent attacks the press has received in Nuevo Laredo, news media have practiced \"self-censorship,\" where local journalist prefer to silence the press and refuse to report on important incidents for fears of reprisals by the cartels.<ref name=silence>{{cite news|last=Castillo|first=Mariano|title=Nuevo Laredo media go silent on violence|url=http://www.chron.com/news/nation-world/article/Nuevo-Laredo-media-go-silent-on-violence-1632204.php|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=29 September 2006}}</ref> Events that would go on the front-page of any newspaper\u2014mass murders with over six dead, shooting incidents wounding three soldiers\u2014often go unreported in Nuevo Laredo.<ref name=silence/> The cartels want the cities they control to appear calm in order to prevent the government from sending federal troops.<ref name=silence/> Consequently, the press, tired of extortions and death threats, prefers to go silent because there is no guarantee for their safety.<ref name=silence/>\n\n==Attacks against casinos==\nOn 21 May 2012, the Mexican authorities were alerted that a casino was on fire in Nuevo Laredo. At around six in the morning, an anonymous call alerted the police that smoke was coming from a building.<ref name=casino>{{cite news|title=Se incendia casino en Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/848603.html|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|date=21 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> By 8:00&nbsp;a.m. the fire had been put down, but a portion of the casino was consumed by the flames.<ref name=casino/> Nonetheless, only material damages were reported.<ref>{{cite news|title=Consume incendio casino clausurado en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2012/05/21/183312201-consume-incendio-casino-clausurado-en-nuevo-laredo|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[La Jornada]]|date=21 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120524045633/http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2012/05/21/183312201-consume-incendio-casino-clausurado-en-nuevo-laredo|archive-date=24 May 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all|language=es}}</ref> Inside the casino were several containers holding large amounts of gasoline, which helped the authorities conclude that the arson was intentional.<ref name=casino/> The 'Amazonas' casino, as it was known, opened in February 2010; however, it was closed in March 2012 for operating illegally.<ref name=casino/> According to the ''[[Blog del Narco]]'', several people from Nuevo Laredo knew that the casino was owned by [[Los Zetas]].<ref name=juega/> The article was also mentioned that the Zetas ordered the closure of another casino known as 'El Juega Juega' to benefit 'Amazonas.'<ref name=juega>{{cite news|title=Incendia el casino Amazonas supuestamente de los Zetas en Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas|url=http://www.mundonarco.com/2012/05/incendia-el-casino-amazonas.html|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[Blog del Narco]]|date=21 May 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130129090258/http://www.mundonarco.com/2012/05/incendia-el-casino-amazonas.html|archive-date=29 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all|language=es}}</ref>\n\nThree days later on 24 May 2012, the 'Maranho' [[nightclub]], considered among the most popular in Nuevo Laredo, was set on fire between 2:00 and 3:00&nbsp;a.m.<ref>{{cite news|title=Incendian bar y estalla veh\u00edculo en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.animalpolitico.com/2012/05/incendian-bar-y-estalla-vehiculo-en-nuevo-laredo/|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=Animal Politico|date=24 May 2012|language=es}}</ref><ref name=maranho>{{cite news|title=Incendian antro y explotan auto en hotel de Nuevo Laredo|url=http://tamaulipas.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/c18034fe3cd5795e5df4a83b70a228ef|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[Milenio]]|date=24 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> And according to unofficial accounts, a group of gunmen were the perpetrators, while some accounts mention that they used grenades and bombs.<ref>{{cite news|title=Reportan ataques en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://noticias.terra.com.mx/mexico/estados/reportan-ataques-en-nuevo-laredo,90ef2a7680087310VgnVCM20000099cceb0aRCRD.html|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[Terra Networks]]|date=24 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> The nightclub was \"completely destroyed,\" but no victims were reported.<ref>{{cite news|title=Se incendia discoteca y explota coche bomba en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://eleconomista.com.mx/seguridad-publica/2012/05/24/se-incendia-discoteca-explota-coche-bomba-nuevo-laredo|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[El Economista (Mexico)|El Economista]]|date=24 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> Other grenade explosions were heard across the border in [[Laredo, Texas]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Incendian discos y granadean hotel en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.zocalo.com.mx/seccion/articulo/incendian-discos-y-granadean-hotel-en-nuevo-laredo|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=Z\u00f3calo|date=24 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> while the residents turned to #LaredoFollow hashtag on [[Twitter]] to report on the violence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nightclubs burned, chaos in the streets of Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?id=757900#.T76iRnlYvDE|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[KGBT-TV]]|date=24 May 2012}}</ref> Unconfirmed reports from [[KGNS-TV]] state that several places in Nuevo Laredo, including educational institutions, are under bomb threats. However, the main targets in the bomb attacks have been entertainment businesses with supposed ties with the mafias that operate in the city.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nuevo Laredo Morning Explosion|url=http://www.pro8news.com/news/local/Nuevo-Laredo-Morning-Explosion--153695805.html|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[KGNS-TV]]|date=24 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528115031/http://www.pro8news.com/news/local/Nuevo-Laredo-Morning-Explosion--153695805.html|archive-date=28 May 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Images==\n{{wide image|ElChapoGuzman-gunmen.jpeg|500px|alt=Sinaloa cartel gunmen|Gunmen of the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] in front of a banner directed to members of [[Los Zetas]] based in Nuevo Laredo. The message was allegedly from [[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]] (\"El Chapo\").}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cadereyta Jim\u00e9nez massacre]]\n* [[2011\u20132012 in the Mexican Drug War]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Mexican Drug War}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nuevo Laredo massacres}}\n[[Category:2012 crimes in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Mexican Drug War]]\n[[Category:Massacres in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 2012]]\n[[Category:Organized crime events in Mexico]]\n[[Category:History of Nuevo Laredo]]\n[[Category:April 2012 events in Mexico]]\n[[Category:May 2012 events in Mexico]]\n[[Category:2012 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2010s murders in Mexico]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title       = 2012 Nuevo Laredo massacres\n| partof      = [[Mexican Drug War]]\n| image       =\n| image_size  = 270px\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Agency image of the hanging cadavers\n| map         =\n| map_size    =\n| map_alt     =\n| map_caption =\n| location    = [[Nuevo Laredo]], [[Tamaulipas]], Mexico\n| target      = \n| fatalities = Unknown\n| coordinates = {{coord|27|29|10|N|99|30|25|W|source:kolossus-nlwiki}}\n| date        = 2012\n| time        = \n| timezone    = \n| type        = [[wikt:turf war|Turf war]]\n| injuries    = Unknown\n| victim      =\n| perps       = [[Sinaloa Cartel]]<br>[[Los Zetas]]<br>[[Gulf Cartel]]\n| perp        =\n| perpetrators= \n| perpetrator = \n| susperps    = \n| susperp     = \n| weapons     = \n| numparts    =\n| numpart     =\n| dfens       =\n| dfen        =\n| footage     =\n| motive      = \n}}\n{{Campaignbox Mexican Drug War}}\nThe '''2012 Nuevo Laredo massacres''' were a series of mass murder attacks between the allied [[Sinaloa Cartel]] and [[Gulf Cartel]] against [[Los Zetas]] in the border city of [[Nuevo Laredo]], [[Tamaulipas]], across the U.S.-Mexico border from [[Laredo, Texas]]. The drug-violence in Nuevo Laredo began back in 2003, when the city was controlled by the [[Gulf Cartel]]. Most media reports that write about the [[Mexican Drug War]], however, point to 2006 as the start of the drug war.<ref name=ioangrillo2004>{{cite book|last=[[Ioan Grillo]]|title=El Narco: The Bloody Rise of Mexican Drug Cartels|year=2012|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Publishing]]|isbn=1408824337|pages=336|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WI08rbJt0oQC&pg=PA94&dq=nuevo+laredo+2004&hl=en&sa=X&ei=GeatT8mON6fD2QWZtrzqCA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=nuevo%20laredo%202004&f=false}}</ref> That year is a convenient historical marker because that's when [[Felipe Calder\u00f3n]] took office and carried out an aggressive approach against the cartels. But authors like [[Ioan Grillo]] and Sylvia Longmire note that Mexico's drug war actually began at the end of [[Vicente Fox]]'s administration in 2004,<ref name=ioangrillo2004/> when the first major battle took place in Nuevo Laredo between the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] and [[Los Zetas]], who at that time worked as the armed wing of the [[Gulf Cartel]].<ref name=ioangrillo2004/><ref name=longmire2004>{{cite news|last=Longmire|first=Sylvia|title=BOOK REVIEW: \"El Narco: Inside Mexico's Criminal Insurgency,\" by Ioan Grillo|url=http://borderviolenceanalysis.typepad.com/mexicos_drug_war/2011/06/book-review-el-narco-by-ioan-grillo.html|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=Mexico's drug war|date=29 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nWhen [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], the former leader of the [[Gulf Cartel]], was arrested in 2003, the [[Sinaloa Cartel]], sensing weakness, tried to move in on Nuevo Laredo, unleashing a bloody battle.<ref name=aploszetas>{{cite news|title=At least 23 people killed in Mexican border city|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5jaEGLgtDqnAWnn89LL9L3Gy48MRQ?docId=17f3dd6b31ca4e56a5e8c9e57a9d375e|accessdate=6 May 2012|agency=Associated Press|date=5 May 2012}}</ref> [[Los Zetas]], however, were successful in expelling the Sinaloa organization out of Nuevo Laredo, and have ruled the city \"with fear\" ever since.<ref name=aploszetas/> Nevertheless, the Gulf cartel and Los Zetas broke relations in early 2010, worsening the violence across northeast Mexico.<ref>{{cite news|title=23 people killed, most decapitated, in Mexican city near US border|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/at-least-23-people-killed-in-mexican-border-city-of-nuevo-laredo-scene-of-drug-cartel-war/2012/05/04/gIQA715J2T_story.html|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|date=4 May 2012}}</ref> The cartels are fighting for control of the corridor in Nuevo Laredo that leads into [[Interstate 35]], one of the most lucrative routes for drug traffickers.<ref name=dallasnews>{{cite news|title=23 killed in Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.dallasnews.com/news/nationworld/mexico/20120504-23-killed-in-nuevo-laredo.ece|accessdate=6 May 2012|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|date=4 May 2012}}</ref> Nuevo Laredo is a lucrative drug corridor because of the large volume of trucks that pass through the area, and the multiple (exploitable) ports of entry.<ref name=longmirecartel>{{cite news|last=Longmire|first=Sylvia|title=Nuevo Laredo heats up as Sinaloa-Zetas conflict leaves 23 dead.|url=http://borderviolenceanalysis.typepad.com/mexicos_drug_war/2012/05/nuevo-laredo-heats-up-as-sinaloa-zetas-conflict-leaves-23-dead.html|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=Mexico's drug war|date=5 May 2012}}</ref> Over 40% of all cargo crossings from Mexico to the United States crosses through the border checkpoints in Nuevo Laredo.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fourteen bodies found in eastern Mexico: officials|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jkZglpMB2jNLQwdlC81JxRXmuBVw?docId=CNG.b2371552eed6d000aa85ebc4c2e4bc6b.781|accessdate=13 June 2012|newspaper=[[Agence France-Presse]]|date=12 June 2012}}</ref> It is for the same reason that [[Tijuana]] and [[Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez]] are so valuable for the drug trafficking organizations.<ref name=longmirecartel/>\n\n==Past incidents in Nuevo Laredo==\n\n===2003 shootout===\nAt around 3&nbsp;am on 1 August 2003, the [[Federal Investigations Agency]] (AFI) confronted a group of armed men in the streets of [[Nuevo Laredo]]. Members of the AFI were staying at a hotel when Juan Manuel Mu\u00f1oz Morales, the attorney general of the city, called for help.<ref name=1abalacera>{{cite news|last=Gonz\u00e1lez |first=Iv\u00e1n |title=Todo sobre el enfrentamiento en Nuevo Laredo |url=http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/305538.html |accessdate=12 May 2012 |newspaper=[[Esmas.com]] |date=1 August 2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123173817/http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/305538.html |archivedate=23 November 2011 |language=es}}</ref> He was reportedly being chased by several individuals in a dark-colored truck. Consequently, the AFI officers followed the truck with seven of their vehicles, triggering a shootout between the police officers and alleged [[drug traffickers]].<ref name=1abalacera/> The armed confrontation lasted for more than 40 minutes, provoking \"panic\" and turning Nuevo Laredo into a \"battlefield.\"<ref name=nvolaredo03>{{cite news|last=Pruneda |first=Salvador |title=Balacera en Nuevo Laredo |url=http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/305170.html |accessdate=12 May 2012 |newspaper=[[Esmas.com]] |date=1 August 2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403060349/http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/305170.html |archivedate=3 April 2010 |language=es}}</ref> The gun detonations were heard throughout most of the city.<ref name=nvolaredo03/> Some witnesses, who preferred to remain anonymous, claimed that they saw over \"18 armed men in black with ski-masks.\"<ref name=nvolaredo03/>\n\nDuring the chase, five armed men in another vehicle shot at the police [[convoy]]. The triggermen in the two vehicles then engaged in a gunfight with the AFI for minutes, but one of the vehicles collided with a police truck. The vehicle the drug traffickers were in then caught on fire, and two of the gunmen were burned to death.<ref name=1abalacera/> The third one died on the sidewalk. According to [[Attorney General of Mexico|PGR]], the three gunmen that were killed were members of [[Los Negros]], a group of hitmen under the tutelage of [[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]] (a.k.a. ''El Chapo'') and of the [[Ju\u00e1rez Cartel]].<ref name=1abalacera/> Rocket-launchers, along with an \"inexact number of assault rifles,\" were reportedly used in the attack.<ref name=nvolaredo03/> In addition, the government agency stated that 198 municipal police officers were to be investigated for possible connections with the [[Gulf Cartel]]; Manuel Mu\u00f1oz, the attorney general who was being chased, was detained by the Mexican authorities. It is believed that he had liberated five members of [[Los Zetas]] who had been detained during the armed confrontation.<ref name=1abalacera/> According to [[Esmas.com]], this shooting was the first major gunfire in Nuevo Laredo between the Mexican authorities and cartel members in over thirty years.<ref>{{cite news|last=L\u00f3pez |first=Primitivo |title=Balacera entre narcos y agentes de la AFI |url=http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/304951.html |accessdate=12 May 2012 |newspaper=[[Esmas.com]] |date=1 August 2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123175140/http://www.esmas.com/noticierostelevisa/mexico/304951.html |archivedate=23 November 2011 |language=es}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1 January and 1 August 2003, 45 homicides were reported in Nuevo Laredo, along with 40 kidnappings.<ref name=nvolaredo03/>\n\n===''El Chapo'' enters Nuevo Laredo===\n[[File:El Chapo-Guzman.jpg|right|200px|thumb|Mug shot of [[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]], ''El Chapo''.]]\nAfter the apprehension of [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] in 2003, the former leader of the [[Gulf Cartel]], his criminal organization went through a leadership crisis, since there was no visible leader to take the lead of the cartel.<ref name=ravelo>{{cite book|last=Ravelo|first=Ricardo|title=El narco en M\u00e9xico|year=2011|publisher=Random House Mondadori|isbn=6073105649|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HAzOTSn5bSYC&pg=PT148&dq=nuevo+laredo+narco&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FPuuT83ZIYi22gWSkPnpCA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=nuevo%20laredo%20narco&f=false|language=es}}</ref> Nonetheless, [[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]], the drug boss of the Sinaloa cartel who is best known as ''El Chapo'', \"broke the rules\" and penetrated into [[Tamaulipas]]. His organization began to kill police officers\u2014forcing many to take a side with or against him\u2014and assassinating rival cartel members. The [[Mexican Armed Forces]] and the program ''M\u00e9xico Seguro'' were unable to put down the violence. For the first time in many years, the Mexican State was limited in its actions\u2014and even surpassed\u2014by the criminal organizations.<ref name=ravelo/> The [[Sinaloa Cartel]] stood to its firm intention to become the \"hegemonic drug trafficking organization in Mexico.\"<ref name=anabel>{{cite book|last=Hern\u00e1ndez|first=Anabel|title=Los se\u00f1ores del narco|year=2012|publisher=Random House Mondadori|isbn=6073108486|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oVLXjMuUrTgC&pg=PP373&dq=nuevo+laredo+narco&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FPuuT83ZIYi22gWSkPnpCA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=nuevo%20laredo%20narco&f=false|language=es}}</ref> And to do so, it had to control the cities along the U.S.-Mexico border. Back in the early 2000s, if a different drug trafficking organization wanted to traffic narcotics through a different corridor, they had to pay a fee to the cartel that controlled it. Hence, it often resulted in a high prize, since [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]] \"knew how much every millimeter in his turf cost.\"<ref name=anabel/>\n\nNo drug trafficking organization before the Sinaloa cartel had dared to take on the [[Gulf Cartel]]. But [[Juan Jos\u00e9 Esparragoza Moreno]] and ''El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n'' were persuasive in moving on into Nuevo Laredo and the rest of Tamaulipas.<ref name=anabel/> One of the first steps in the war between the Gulf and Sinaloa cartels began when [[Arturo Beltr\u00e1n Leyva]], alias ''El Barbas'', hired Dionisio Rom\u00e1n Garc\u00eda (''El Chacho''), the leader of a gang who operated in [[Nuevo Laredo]] under the permission of Osiel in 2002. Nevertheless, ''El Chacho'' turned against the Osiel and the Gulf organization by deciding to work for the Sinaloa cartel and killing a Zeta member. This triggered a series of attacks and executions in [[Tamaulipas]].<ref name=anabel/> And, in order to put down the violence, ''El Barbas'' sought [[Arturo Guzm\u00e1n Decena]], one of the founders of Los Zetas, and told him that he \"did not want any problems\" with the [[Los Zetas|Zetas]], and that he would do his best to turn in ''El Chacho''. Guzm\u00e1n Decena accepted his apology, but told him that if anyone from the Sinaloa cartel wanted to traffic drugs inside the Gulf Cartel's territory, they had to be unarmed and under supervision.<ref name=anabel/>\n\nIn May 2002, ''El Chacho'' was kidnapped in the city of [[Monterrey]] by members of Los Zetas, and eventually found dead in Tamaulipas, bearing signs of torture.<ref name=ravelo/><ref>{{cite news|title=Identifican a ejecutados en Nuevo Le\u00f3n|url=http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/26270.html|accessdate=13 May 2012|newspaper=El Siglo de Torreon|date=4 April 2003|language=es}}</ref> ''El Barbas'' then asked Osiel if [[Edgar Valdez Villarreal]] (''La Barbie'') could replace ''El Chacho'', and he accepted. [[Los Zetas]], however, were not convinced nor happy with Osiel's decision, because for them, \"a betrayal is a betrayal.\"<ref name=anabel/> Fifteen days after the capture of Osiel, Valdez Villarreal called [[Heriberto Lazcano Lazcano]] (who had taken the lead of Los Zetas after the death of Guzm\u00e1n Decena in 2002) and said: \"You have a week to leave the territories from [[Reynosa]] to [[Nuevo Laredo]].\" With this, the war had started.<ref name=anabel/>\n\n==2012 incursions==\n{{Main|2011\u20132012 in the Mexican Drug War|Mexican Drug War}}\n\n===17 April 2012 massacre===\nDismembered remains of 14 men were found in several plastic bags inside a [[Chrysler Voyager#Generation III|Chrysler Voyager]] in the border city of [[Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas|Nuevo Laredo]], [[Tamaulipas]] on 17 April 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexico authorities say bodies of 14 men dumped in Nuevo Laredo|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/world_now/2012/04/bodies-of-14-men-dumped-in-mexican-border-city.html|accessdate=18 April 2012|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=17 April 2012}}</ref> All of those killed were between the ages of 30 and 35.<ref>{{cite news|title=Localizan 14 cad\u00e1veres dentro de veh\u00edculo abandonado en Nuevo Laredo |url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/667913268f5737dec48f486e722aaf30 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120904062639/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/667913268f5737dec48f486e722aaf30 |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 September 2012 |accessdate=18 April 2012 |newspaper=[[Milenio]] |date=17 April 2012 |language=es}}</ref> Mexican officials stated that they found a \"messaged signed by a criminal group,\" but they did not release the content of the note,<ref>{{cite news|title=14 mutilated bodies found in Mexican border city |url=http://www.elpasotimes.com/juarez/ci_20419518/14-mutilated-bodies-found-mexican-border-city |accessdate=18 April 2012 |newspaper=[[El Paso Times]] |date=17 April 2012 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> nor if those killed were members of Los Zetas or of the [[Gulf Cartel]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Mosso |first=Rub\u00e9n |title=Nuevo Laredo: hallan 14 cuerpos mutilados |url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/667913268f5737dec48f486e725f91a7 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130104011548/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/667913268f5737dec48f486e725f91a7 |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 January 2013 |accessdate=18 April 2012 |newspaper=[[Milenio]] |date=18 April 2012 |language=es}}</ref> ''[[CNN en Espa\u00f1ol|CNNM\u00e9xico]]'' stated that the message left behind by the criminal group said that they were going to \"clean up Nuevo Laredo\" by killing Zeta members.<ref>{{cite news|title=14 cuerpos mutilados fueron hallados en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://blogs.cnnmexico.com/ultimas-noticias/2012/04/17/14-cuerpos-mutilados-fueron-hallados-en-nuevo-laredo/|accessdate=18 April 2012|newspaper=[[CNN en Espa\u00f1ol|CNNM\u00e9xico]]|date=17 April 2012|language=es}}</ref> ''[[The Monitor (Texas)|The Monitor]]'' newspaper, however, said that a source outside law enforcement but with direct knowledge of the attacks stated the 14 bodies belonged to members of [[Los Zetas]] who had been killed by the [[Jalisco New Generation Cartel]], now a branch of the [[Sinaloa Cartel]].<ref>{{cite news|title=14 bodies found in minivan outside Nuevo Laredo City Hall, according to Tamps. gov't |url=http://www.themonitor.com/articles/bodies-60209-hall-city.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427034103/http://www.themonitor.com/articles/bodies-60209-hall-city.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 April 2012 |accessdate=18 April 2012 |newspaper=[[The Monitor (Texas)|The Monitor]] |date=17 April 2012 }}</ref> Following the attacks, the Sinaloa cartel's kingpin, [[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]]\u2014better known as ''El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n''\u2014sent a message to [[Los Zetas]] that they will fight for the control of the Nuevo Laredo plaza.<ref>{{cite news|title=El Chapo demuestra su poder en Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas |url=http://www.blogdelnarco.com/2012/04/el-chapo-demuestra-su-poder-en-nuevo-laredo-tamps/ |accessdate=18 April 2012 |newspaper=[[Blog del Narco]] |date=18 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120420210702/http://www.blogdelnarco.com/2012/04/el-chapo-demuestra-su-poder-en-nuevo-laredo-tamps/ |archivedate=20 April 2012 |language=es}}</ref> The message read the following:\n{{Quotation|\"We have begun to clear Nuevo Laredo of Zetas because we want a free city and so you can live in peace. We are narcotics traffickers and we don't mess with honest working or business people. I'm going to teach these scums to work Sinaloa style\u2014without kidnapping, without payoffs, without extortion. As for you, 40, I tell you that you don't scare me. I know you sent H to toss heads here in my turf, because you don't have the stones nor the people to do it yourself. Don't forget that I'm your true father.\"| [[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]], <small>(El Chapo)</small><ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Dane|title=Drug lord \"El Chapo\" declares war on Zetas|url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Drug-lord-El-Chapo-declares-war-on-Zetas-3492866.php|accessdate=19 April 2012|newspaper=[[The Houston Chronicle]]|date=18 April 2012}}</ref>}}\n\n[[Nuevo Laredo]] is considered a stronghold of Los Zetas,<ref>{{cite news|title=Mexican authorities find 14 dead in Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2012/04/mexican-authorities-find-14-dead-in.html|accessdate=18 April 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=17 April 2012}}</ref> although there were incursions by the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] in March 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=El Chapo Guzm\u00e1n comienza limpia de Los Zetas en Tamaulipas|url=http://www.blogdelnarco.com/2012/03/el-chapo-guzman-comienza-limpia-de-los-zetas-en-tamaulipas/|accessdate=18 April 2012|newspaper=[[Blog del Narco]]|date=26 March 2012|language=es}}</ref><ref name=insightnuevolaredo1>{{cite news|last=Corcoran |first=Patrick |title='Narcomantas' Herald Chapo's Incursion into Mexico Border State |url=http://insightcrime.org/insight-latest-news/item/2414-narcomantas-herald-chapos-incursion-into-mexico-border-state |accessdate=18 April 2012 |newspaper=[[InSight Crime]] |date=28 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120409054719/http://insightcrime.org/insight-latest-news/item/2414-narcomantas-herald-chapos-incursion-into-mexico-border-state |archivedate=9 April 2012 }}</ref> Consequently, Los Zetas responded two days later with incursions to [[Sinaloa]], the homestate of the Sinaloa Cartel.<ref>{{cite news|last=Martinez|first=Chivis|title=Z40 Answers Chapo by Leaving His Own Butchery and Message|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2012/03/z40-answers-chapo-by-leaving-his-own.html|accessdate=19 April 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=28 March 2012}}</ref> The Sinaloa Cartel's first attempt to take over Nuevo Laredo happened in 2005, when [[Los Zetas]] was working as the armed wing of the [[Gulf Cartel]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Schiller|first=Dane|title=Is 'El Chapo' back in border city of Nuevo Laredo?|url=http://blog.chron.com/narcoconfidential/2012/04/with-butchery-and-a-warning-is-mexicos-el-chapo-back-in-border-city-of-nuevo-laredo/|accessdate=19 April 2012|newspaper=[[The Houston Chronicle]]|date=18 April 2012}}</ref>\n;InSight Crime analysis\n[[File:NuevoLaredo-narcokillings.jpg|left|180px|thumb|Front page of the killings in [[Nuevo Laredo]].]]\nThe \"40\" in the message is a reference to [[Miguel Trevi\u00f1o Morales]], a top leader of Los Zetas based in Nuevo Laredo, and longtime adversary of ''El Chapo'' Guzm\u00e1n. The \"H\" is presumably [[H\u00e9ctor Beltr\u00e1n Leyva]], the last remaining brother of the [[Beltr\u00e1n Leyva Cartel]].<ref name=insightanalysis>{{cite news|last=Corcoran|first=Patrick|title=Bodies, Banner Herald Sinaloa Cartel's Push East|url=http://insightcrime.org/insight-latest-news/item/2529-more-evidence-of-chapos-arrival-in-mexico-border-town|accessdate=24 April 2012|newspaper=[[InSight Crime]]|date=23 April 2012}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The Beltr\u00e1n Leyva organization, unlike the Zetas, has presence in Sinaloa state, and would probably have an easier time attacking the Sinaloa Cartel on its own turf. The message does not mention the fact that the [[Gulf Cartel]] is probably supporting the Sinaloa Cartel in carrying out the executions.<ref name=insightanalysis/> In addition, the banner suggests that the alliance between Los Zetas and the Beltr\u00e1n Leyva Cartel remains intact as of 2012 despite its losses it lived in 2008. The message also suggests the differences in the modus operandi of [[Los Zetas]] and the [[Sinaloa Cartel]], because as authors of InSight Crime allege, the Zetas have a reputation of operating through extortions, kidnappings, robberies, and other illicit activities; in contrast, the Sinaloa Cartel is known simply for drug trafficking. (Both assertions are not wholly true, but often reflect a popular sentiment). Guzm\u00e1n attempted to take over Nuevo Laredo after the capture of the Gulf Cartel leader, [[Osiel C\u00e1rdenas Guill\u00e9n]], in 2003.<ref name=insightanalysis/>\n\nNevertheless, Guzm\u00e1n retreated after a few years of bloody turf wars. The Sinaloa Cartel's return to Nuevo Laredo, however, was seen again in March 2012 after Guzm\u00e1n reportedly left several corpses and a message heralding his return.<ref name=insightnuevolaredo1/> According to the [[Bureau of Transportation Statistics]], Nuevo Laredo is the busiest border crossing in terms of truck crossings with over 1.7 million trucks a year, more than double than any other crossing in the Mexico\u2013United States border.<ref name=bts>{{cite web|title=Border Crossing/Entry Data: Quick Search by Rankings|url=http://www.bts.gov/programs/international/transborder/TBDR_BC/TBDR_BC_QuickSearch.html|publisher=[[Bureau of Transportation Statistics]]|accessdate=24 April 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702013155/http://www.bts.gov/programs/international/transborder/TBDR_BC/TBDR_BC_QuickSearch.html|archive-date=2 July 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Nuevo Laredo is the fourth-busiest border crossing in terms of passenger vehicles.<ref name=bts/> Patrick Corcoran of InSight Crime believes that the turf war in Nuevo Laredo will bring a huge wave of violence, but also mentioned that the circumstances have changed since the split of the [[Gulf Cartel]] and [[Los Zetas]] in early 2010. The current alliance between Guzm\u00e1n's Sinaloa Cartel and the Gulf Cartel may successfully extract Los Zetas and give ''El Chapo'' the upper hand.\n\nAnd once the Sinaloa Cartel gets established in Nuevo Laredo, it may possibly make moves to control [[Reynosa]] and [[Matamoros, Tamaulipas]].<ref name=insightanalysis/>\n\n;Investigations\nOn 24 April 2012, the attorney general of the state of [[Tamaulipas]] identified 10 of the 14 people killed. In addition, the Mexican authorities stated that those killed had \"no relationship with the criminal group [[Los Zetas]],\" and that they were in fact innocent civilians.<ref name=lapoliciacainnocentes>{{cite news|title=Desligan al \"Chapo Guzman\" de la masacre en Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas|url=http://www.lapoliciaca.com/nota-roja/desligan-al-chapo-guzman-de-la-masacre-en-nuevo-laredo-tamaulipas/|accessdate=26 April 2012|newspaper=La Policiaca|date=24 April 2012|language=es}}</ref> The [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] indicated that 7 out of the 14 who were killed were reportedly deported immigrants who were working illegally in the United States.<ref name=lapoliciacainnocentes/> The authorities said that the massacre was carried out to generate \"psychosis,\" because there is no concrete evidence of a \"war between drug cartels\" nor elements that indicate the presence of a group representing the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] in the border city of Nuevo Laredo.<ref>{{cite news|title=Desligan a Chapo de masacre de N. Laredo|url=http://noticias.terra.com.mx/mexico/estados/desligan-a-chapo-de-masacre-de-n-laredo,41a982f1b07e6310VgnVCM10000098cceb0aRCRD.html|accessdate=26 April 2012|newspaper=[[Terra Networks]]|date=24 April 2012|language=es}}</ref><ref name=guerraentrecarteles/> Some of the bodies have been returned to their families.<ref>{{cite news|last=Guzm\u00e1n|first=Julio Manuel|title=Identifican a 7 de 14 asesinados en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/843349.html|accessdate=26 April 2012|newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|date=24 April 2012|language=es}}</ref> The rest of the corpses have not been identified and remain in the Forensic Medical Services (SEMEFO).<ref name=guerraentrecarteles>{{cite news|title=Identifican a 7 de los 14 asesinados en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.noticiasdetamaulipas.com/nota.cgi?id=410791|accessdate=27 April 2012|newspaper=Noticias de Tamaulipas|date=24 April 2012|language=es}}</ref>\n\n===4 May 2012 massacre===\n23 bodies\u201414 of them decapitated and 9 of them hanged from a bridge\u2014were discovered in [[Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas]], in an escalation of brutal violence involving rival drug gangs on the U.S. border.<ref name=nuevecolgados/> In the first incident, at around 1:00&nbsp;am on 4 May 2012, nine people were hanged from a bridge on the [[Mexican Federal Highway 85D]] with a message left behind by the killers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Los cuerpos de 23 personas son encontrados en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2012/05/04/los-cuerpos-de-23-personas-son-encontrados-en-nuevo-laredo|accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=CNNM\u00e9xico|date=4 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> Horrified motorists encountered the blood-stained bodies of four women and five men hanging off a bridge.<ref name=golfas/><ref>{{cite news|title=23 dead in day of horror for Mexico border city|url=http://au.news.yahoo.com/world/a/-/world/13608544/23-dead-in-day-of-horror-for-mexico-border-city/|accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=[[Yahoo! News]]|date=4 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120516195543/http://au.news.yahoo.com/world/a/-/world/13608544/23-dead-in-day-of-horror-for-mexico-border-city/|archive-date=16 May 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The banner left behind reportedly stated that those killed were the perpetrators of the car bomb in the city on 24 April 2012.<ref name=nuevecolgados>{{cite news|title=Nuevo Laredo vive un viernes negro, jornada violenta deja 23 muertos|url=http://excelsior.com.mx/index.php?m=nota&seccion=seccion-nacional&cat=1&id_nota=831656|accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]|date=4 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> In addition, the 9 people who were hanged on the bridge were reportedly members of the [[Gulf Cartel]] who were killed by [[Los Zetas]] for \"heating up\" their turf.<ref>{{cite news|title=Suman 23 muertos en Nuevo Laredo, entre colgados y decapitados|url=http://noticias.univision.com/narcotrafico/noticias/article/2012-05-04/nueve-cuerpos-colgados-puente-nuevo-laredo-mexico-narco-zetas#axzz1tvkHuxlD|accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=[[Univision]]|date=4 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> The message read the following:\n{{Quotation|\"Fucking ([[Gulf Cartel]]) whores, this is how I'm going to finish off every fucker you send to heat up the turf. You have to fuck up sometime and that's when I'm gonna put you in your place. We are going to fuck up ''El Gringo'' that keeps setting off [[car bombs]]; the fucker Juanito Carrizales and his friend ''El Tubi'', who I killed because he kept crying like a bitch; ''El Metro 4'' who asked Comandante [[Heriberto Lazcano Lazcano|Lazcano]] for mercy when he was kicking the shit out of him; and now ''[[Juan Mej\u00eda Gonz\u00e1lez|El R1]]'' in [[Reynosa]] and you. But it's okay, here are your guys. The rest went away but I'll get them. Sooner or later. See you around fuckers.<ref name=golfas>{{cite news|title=Ejecutan y cuelgan a nueve personas en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.blogdelnarco.com/2012/05/ejecutan-y-cuelgan-a-nueve-personas-en-nuevo-laredo/|accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=[[Blog del Narco]]|date=4 May 2012|language=es}}</ref>| [[Los Zetas]]}}\n\nIn the second incident, which occurred hours later, 14 decapitated bodies were abandoned inside a vehicle in front of the Customs Agency;<ref name=universal23/> the severed heads were left inside several ice coolers in front of the municipal palace.<ref name=universal23>{{cite news|title=Van 23 muertos en Nuevo Laredo, en ola de violencia|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/845350.html|accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|date=4 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> The Mexican police said the second massacre could have been an act of revenge by the [[Gulf Cartel]] to Los Zetas for the earlier killings.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bodies of 23 found dumped near U.S. border in Mexico drug war|url=https://news.yahoo.com/nine-bodies-hung-bridge-northern-mexico-174942376.html|accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=[[Yahoo! News]]|date=4 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Se recrudece violencia en Nuevo Laredo: 23 muertos|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/estados/85705.html|accessdate=5 May 2012|newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|date=5 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> Along with the decapitated bodies was a message allegedly signed by [[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]], where he demanded the municipality mayor of [[Nuevo Laredo]], Benjam\u00edn Galv\u00e1n, along with other municipal and state leaders and public safety officials to recognize the Sinaloa cartel's presence in the area and stop insisting he is not in the city.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pide \"El Chapo Guzman\" al alcalde de Nuevo Laredo que deje de negar su presencia|url=http://www.lapoliciaca.com/nota-roja/pide-el-chapo-guzman-al-alcalde-de-nuevo-laredo-que-deje-de-negar-su-presencia/|accessdate=6 May 2012|newspaper=La Policiaca|date=6 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> The message read the following:\n{{Quotation|\"You want credibility that I am in [[Nuevo Laredo|NL]]?  What will it take, bringing the heads of [[Los Zetas|Zeta]] leaders?  Or yours? Mr. [Benjam\u00edn Galv\u00e1n], since you want to give us a sweet treat, with you coming out saying that nothing is happening here and all is well, continue with the same and I assure you that heads will keep rolling. Keep making [[Miguel Trevi\u00f1o Morales|Z-40]]'s case to say and deny that we already operate in [[Nuevo Laredo]], just so that [[Heriberto Lazcano Lazcano|Lazcano]] will not scold this illiterate car washer. And you [Alfonso Olvera], Director of Public Security appointed entirely by Z-40, who is your buddy, keep declaring that my staff does not operate here in Nuevo Laredo. Or you, [V\u00edctor Almanza], stating that the dismembered were masons, traders, migrants or simple and humble workers (and not what they were [[Los Zetas|Zetas]]). Continue to deny my presence here in [[Nuevo Laredo]] and you will continue to see their heads. I do not kill innocent people to submit work as you are accustomed [[Miguel Trevi\u00f1o Morales|Z-40]], all dead in Nuevo Laredo are pure scums, in other words, pure [[Los Zetas|Z]]. Sincerely, your father.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Chapo Leaves Message with Decapitated Bodies Issues Threat against NL Mayor|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2012/05/chapo-leaves-message-with-decapitated.html|accessdate=6 May 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=6 May 2012}}</ref>|[[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]], <small>(El Chapo)</small>}}\n\n==Car bomb attacks==\nAt around 8:00&nbsp;a.m. on 24 April 2012 in [[Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas]], a car bomb exploded outside the city's police department.<ref>{{cite news|title=Car bomb explosion followed by shootout in Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?id=745672#.T5eVxcS3CFc|accessdate=25 April 2012|newspaper=[[KGBT-TV]]|date=24 April 2012}}</ref> When the Mexican military arrived at the area of the explosion, they engaged in a confrontation with cartel members who shot them upon their arrival.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coche bomba y enfrentamiento en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/843249.html|accessdate=25 April 2012|newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|date=24 April 2012|language=es}}</ref> There was one civilian who was injured as a result of the car bomb.<ref>{{cite news|title=Confirman coche-bomba en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://noticias.terra.com.mx/mexico/seguridad/confirman-coche-bomba-en-nuevo-laredo,7cc0b7efda6e6310VgnVCM5000009ccceb0aRCRD.html|accessdate=25 April 2012|newspaper=[[Terra Networks]]|date=24 April 2012|language=es}}</ref> The ''[[Blog del Narco]]'' credited the attacks to [[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]] (a.k.a. ''El Chapo''), who reportedly left another message for [[Los Zetas]] about the Sinaloa cartel's incursion in Nuevo Laredo.<ref>{{cite news|title=Reafirma El Chapo presencia en Tamaulipas con coche bomba|url=http://www.blogdelnarco.com/2012/04/reafirma-el-chapo-presencia-en-tamulipas-con-coche-bomba/|accessdate=25 April 2012|newspaper=[[Blog del Narco]]|date=24 April 2012|language=es}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cochebomba-Nuevo Laredo.jpeg|right|260px|thumb|[[Car bomb]] explosion outside the city hall in Nuevo Laredo.]]\nIn the second incident, suspected members of a drug trafficking organization opened fire at a hotel that the [[Federal Police (Mexico)|Federal police]] was using as barracks on 23 May 2012, and then set off a car bomb in front of the police dormitories.<ref>{{cite news|title=Photos of damage from hotel car bombing in Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?id=758095#.T8AdJHlYvDE|accessdate=26 May 2012|newspaper=[[KGBT-TV]]|date=24 May 2012}}</ref><ref name=zetasbomb/> A Chevrolet pickup truck exploded at around 5:30&nbsp;a.m. inside the parking lot of Hotel Santa Cecilia in southern Nuevo Laredo, injuring 2 civilians and 8 police officers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Estalla coche bomba en Nuevo Laredo; 8 polic\u00edas y 2 civiles resultaron heridos|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2012/05/25/index.php?section=politica&article=016n1pol&partner=rss|accessdate=25 May 2012|newspaper=[[La Jornada]]|date=25 May 2012|language=es}}</ref><ref name=valenciabomb>{{cite news|last=Valencia|first=Nick|title=Gun and bomb attack on hotel in Mexican border town wounds 10|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/05/25/world/americas/mexico-violence/|accessdate=25 May 2012|newspaper=[[CNN International]]|date=25 May 2012}}</ref> The blast was strong enough to partially damage several rooms in the hotel and a couple of vehicles.<ref name=valenciabomb/><ref>{{cite news|title=Estalla coche bomba en Nuevo Laredo; al menos 10 heridos|url=http://excelsior.com.mx/index.php?m=nota&seccion=seccion-nacional&cat=1&id_nota=836523|accessdate=25 May 2012|newspaper=[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]|date=24 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> Three of the ten police officers were wounded with third degree burns in half of their bodies, while the rest were treated for non-life-threatening wounds.<ref name=valenciabomb/> Many residents living in Nuevo Laredo and across the international border in [[Laredo, Texas]] were reportedly awaken by the car explosion.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bomb in Mexico felt in Texas|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/article/Bomb-in-Mexico-felt-in-Texas-3584541.php|accessdate=25 May 2012|newspaper=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|date=24 May 2012}}</ref> Some Laredo residents also began calling [[9-1-1]] early in the morning as the cartel battles in Nuevo Laredo reached their peak.<ref name=shook/> One resident even said that the explosions in Nuevo Laredo made his house shake across the border.<ref name=shook>{{cite news|title=Laredo Residents Wake Up To Sounds of Explosions, Gunfire|url=http://www.pro8news.com/news/local/Laredo-Residents-Wake-Up-To-Sounds-of-Explosions-Gunfire-153803235.html|accessdate=25 May 2012|newspaper=[[KGNS-TV]]|date=24 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528114917/http://www.pro8news.com/news/local/Laredo-Residents-Wake-Up-To-Sounds-of-Explosions-Gunfire-153803235.html|archive-date=28 May 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Soon after the attacks, the [[Mexican Army]] put up a military checkpoint in the avenue where the hotel is situated.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coche bomba explota en hotel en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://eleconomista.com.mx/seguridad-publica/2012/05/24/coche-bomba-explota-hotel-nuevo-laredo|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[El Economista (Mexico)|El Economista]]|date=24 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> In addition, this attack was the first attack directed to Tamaulipas' new state police force, which took over the duties of the municipal police forces that were considered ineffective and corrupt.<ref>{{cite news|last=Weissenstein|first=Michael|title=Mexico Gang Launches Car Bomb Near US Border|url=http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/mexico-gang-launches-car-bomb-us-border-16426137#.T7_IV3lYvDE|accessdate=25 May 2012|newspaper=[[ABC News]]|date=24 May 2012}}</ref> The authorities in the Mexican state of Tamaulipas believe that [[Los Zetas]], one of Mexico's most powerful criminal groups, carried out the attack. Los Zetas are known for carrying out a number of attacks, but this one was described as \"one of the most elaborate.\"<ref name=zetasbomb>{{cite news|title=Mexico gang launches car bomb near US border|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5jFT8jVncDy-KLN8GVOVBDsm86LNg?docId=771194735b844dc19c892c1153c89dd8|accessdate=25 May 2012|newspaper=[[Associated Press]]|date=25 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nA third car bomb was abandoned on 29 June 2012 in front of the municipal palace at around 11:00&nbsp;a.m., and exploded just below the office of Benjam\u00edn Galv\u00e1n G\u00f3mez, the mayor of Nuevo Laredo.<ref name=ventana>{{cite news|title=Estallan auto frente a Palacio en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/856428.html|accessdate=29 June 2012|newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|date=29 June 2012|language=es}}</ref> Explosives were planted inside a gray [[Ford Ranger]] pickup truck, damaging more than ten vehicles that were parked near the car bomb and destroying dozens of windows in its surroundings.<ref name=ventana/><ref name=salaredo>{{cite news|last=Buch|first=Jason|title=Car bomb rocks Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/local_news/article/Car-bomb-rocks-Nuevo-Laredo-3673813.php|accessdate=29 June 2012|newspaper=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|date=29 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=H\u00e9ctor|title=Coche bomba estalla frente a alcald\u00eda de Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/index.php?m=nota&seccion=seccion-nacional&cat=28&id_nota=844445&rss=1|accessdate=29 June 2012|newspaper=[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]|date=29 June 2012}}</ref> The detonation was heard on both sides of the U.S.-Mexico border.<ref>{{cite news|title=Possible Car Bomb at Nuevo Laredo City Hall|url=http://www.pro8news.com/news/local/Possible-Car-Bomb-at-Nuevo-Laredo-City-Hall-160854945.html|accessdate=29 June 2012|newspaper=[[KGNS-TV]]|date=29 June 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130131232937/http://www.pro8news.com/news/local/Possible-Car-Bomb-at-Nuevo-Laredo-City-Hall-160854945.html|archive-date=31 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Laredo police said they received calls from several residents reporting an explosion, and dispatched officiers to the [[international bridges in Laredo, Texas|international bridges]] in the Texan city. A plume of smoke was seen from the U.S. side too.<ref name=salaredo/> In addition, seven people who were near the explosion were injured.<ref name=expression>{{cite news|title=Siete lesionados por granadazo: Gobierno de Tamaulipas|url=http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/dbd1ce87b7901fd6e2aa1bc5f7e32f42|accessdate=29 June 2012|newspaper=[[Milenio]]|date=29 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120701154141/http://www.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/dbd1ce87b7901fd6e2aa1bc5f7e32f42|archive-date=1 July 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all|language=es}}</ref> The Federal police and the Mexican Army cordoned the crime scene, as paramedics stabilized the bystanders and transported them to the nearest hospital.<ref>{{cite news|title=Car bomb wounds 7 in Mexican border city|url=http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/news/2012/06/29/car-bomb-wounds-7-in-mexican-border-city/|accessdate=29 June 2012|newspaper=[[Fox News]]|date=29 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304063149/http://latino.foxnews.com/latino/news/2012/06/29/car-bomb-wounds-7-in-mexican-border-city/|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The Mexican authorities believe this car bomb attack was a form of \"expression\" by the criminal syndicates who operate in Nuevo Laredo and want to make their presence known.<ref name=expression/> The state of Tamaulipas pledged to intensify the security measures in Nuevo Laredo.<ref>{{cite news|title=Un coche bomba explota frente al edificio municipal de Nuevo Laredo|url=http://mexico.cnn.com/nacional/2012/06/29/un-coche-bomba-explota-frente-al-edificio-municipal-de-nuevo-laredo|accessdate=29 June 2012|newspaper=CNNM\u00e9xico|date=29 June 2012|language=es}}</ref>\n\n==Attacks against the media==\n{{See also|List of journalists killed in the Mexican Drug War}}\nOn 19 March 2004, journalist [[Roberto Javier Mora Garc\u00eda]] was stabbed 26 times outside his home in Nuevo Laredo.<ref>{{cite web|title=El asesinato de Roberto Mora Garc\u00eda, director editorial de \"El Ma\u00f1ana\", lleva cinco a\u00f1os impune|url=http://www.ifex.org/mexico/2009/03/24/murder_of_newspaper_director_robert/es/|publisher=[[International Freedom of Expression Exchange]]|accessdate=12 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> On 6 February 2006, two armed men broke into the offices of ''El Ma\u00f1ana'' and detonated a grenade.<ref name=terra2006>{{cite news|title=Diario \"El Ma\u00f1ana\" de Nuevo Laredo sufre atentado|url=http://noticias.terra.com.mx/mexico/seguridad/diario-el-manana-de-nuevo-laredo-sufre-atentado,34eb1273c1147310VgnVCM4000009bcceb0aRCRD.html|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[Terra Networks]]|date=12 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> They also shot the outside walls of the installation with [[AK-47]]s and [[AR-15]]s before fleeing the scene.<ref name=terra2006/> According to ''[[La Jornada]]'', the armed men shot the installation more than 100 times, injuring Jaime Orozco Tey, a journalist.<ref>{{cite news|title=Irrupci\u00f3n armada en el peri\u00f3dico El Ma\u00f1ana de Nuevo Laredo; un herido|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2006/02/07/index.php?section=politica&article=022n1pol|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[La Jornada]]|date=6 February 2006|language=es}}</ref> On 30 July 2010, a group of armed men in a vehicle threw a grenade at the offices of [[Televisa]] in Nuevo Laredo, damaging two vehicles.<ref>{{cite news|title=Atacan El Ma\u00f1ana de Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.elmanana.com/diario/noticia/tamaulipas/noticias/atacan_el_manana_de_nuevo_laredo/1620047|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=El Ma\u00f1ana|date=12 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> On 26 September 2011, Mar\u00eda Elizabeth Mac\u00edas Castro, an editor of la ''Primera Hora'' newspaper, was decapitated; a note was left behind by Los Zetas, claiming responsibility for the killing.<ref>{{cite news|last=Chapa|first=Sergio|title=Journalist group condemns Nuevo Laredo editor's murder|url=http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?id=667650#.T66yHZ9YvDE|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[KGBT-TV]]|date=29 September 2011}}</ref> The message read the following: \"For those who don't want to believe, this happened to [Mar\u00eda Elizabeth Mac\u00edas Castro] because of [her] actions, for believing in the army and the navy. Thank you for your attention, respectfully, [[Los Zetas]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Another social media killing in Nuevo Laredo|url=http://blog.mysanantonio.com/beyondtheborder/2011/09/another-social-media-killing-in-nuevo-laredo/|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|date=27 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Attacks against bloggers and social media users===\nOn 13 September 2011, a man and a woman in their early twenties were hanged from a pedestrian bridge in Nuevo Laredo.<ref name=septembertwit>{{cite news|last=Castillo |first=Mariano |title=Bodies hanging from bridge in Mexico are warning to social media users |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2011-09-14/world/mexico.violence_1_zetas-cartel-social-media-users-nuevo-laredo?_s=PM:WORLD |accessdate=12 May 2012 |publisher=CNN |date=14 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510001812/http://articles.cnn.com/2011-09-14/world/mexico.violence_1_zetas-cartel-social-media-users-nuevo-laredo?_s=PM%3AWORLD |archivedate=10 May 2012 }}</ref> Their fingers and ears were mutilated, and both bore signs of torture.<ref name=septembertwit/> The signs left behind declared that the pair were killed for posting denouncements of the drug cartel activities on the Internet.<ref name=balconear>{{cite news|title=Balconear a criminales en Internet firm\u00f3 su sentencia de muerte|url=http://www.excelsior.com.mx/index.php?m=nota&seccion=&cat=&id_nota=768253|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[Exc\u00e9lsior]]|date=14 September 2011|language=es}}</ref> The message read: \"This is going to happen to all of those posting funny things on the Internet,\" one sign said. \"You better (expletive) pay attention. I'm about to get you.\"<ref name=septembertwit/> The killing was carried out by [[Los Zetas]].<ref name=septembertwit/> \nOn 9 November 2011, a blogger was tortured and decapitated for allegedly denouncing against the organized crime groups online.<ref name=rascatripa/> The man killed reportedly used the username \"Rascatripa\" in the site known as ''Nuevo Laredo en Vivo'', where civilians post on the activities of [[Los Zetas]].<ref name=rascatripa>{{cite news|title=Decapitan a cibernauta; van cuatro en dos meses|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=287540|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]|date=9 November 2011|language=es}}</ref> The killers left another message on top of the corpse stating the following: \"Hello! I'm Rascatripas and this happened to me for failing to understand that I should not report things on social media websites. With this last report I bid farewell to Nuevo Laredo en Vivo.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Nuevo Laredo: Man tortured and decapitated for allegedly denouncing cartel activity online|url=http://www.borderlandbeat.com/2011/11/nuevo-laredo-man-tortured-and.html|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[Borderland Beat]]|date=9 November 2011}}</ref> This man was the fourth killed by the cartels for posting against them on the Internet in less than two months.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fitch|first=Nubia|title=Asesinan a otro usuario de redes sociales|url=http://www.sexenio.com.mx/articulo.php?id=10644|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=Sexenio|date=9 November 2011|language=es}}</ref> The brutal killings sent \"shock waves\" to the online community, and Twitter users from [[Nuevo Laredo]], [[Reynosa]], and the [[Rio Grande Valley]], along with other border communities, issued a joint statement asking for protection in November 2011.<ref name=rgvcomplain>{{cite news|last=Sergio|first=Chapa|title=Twitter users want justice after fourth social media murder in Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?id=685186#.T67GwZ9YvDE|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[KGBT-TV]]|date=10 November 2011}}</ref> The bloggers asked the Mexican government to solve the murders and protect freedom of speech.<ref name=rgvcomplain/> Even the \"hacker group\" known as [[Anonymous (group)|Anonymous]] stepped in and gave recommendations to the community in Nuevo Laredo to \"be careful\" when denouncing Los Zetas.<ref>{{cite news|last=Althaus|first=Dudley|title=Gang sends message with blogger beheading|url=http://www.chron.com/news/nation-world/article/Gang-sends-message-with-blogger-beheading-2260814.php|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=11 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Cartels silence the media===\nIn another incident, a group of armed men attacked the offices of ''[[El Ma\u00f1ana (Nuevo Laredo)|El Ma\u00f1ana]]'' newspaper at around 23:00 hours on 11 May 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ataca comando a peri\u00f3dico en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/846811.html|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|date=12 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> The Mexican authorities stated that no one was injured in the 5-minute shootout, but the offices and some vehicles were damaged when bullets impacted from the outside.<ref>{{cite news|title=Armed men open fire on Mexican newspaper office in border city of Nuevo Laredo|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/armed-men-open-fire-on-mexican-newspaper-office-in-border-city-of-nuevo-laredo/2012/05/12/gIQApi3TJU_story.html|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|date=12 May 2012}}</ref> When the employees of ''El Ma\u00f1ana'' heard the detonations, they threw themselves on the floor, while others suffered nervous breakdowns.<ref>{{cite news|title=Comando ataca a balazos el peri\u00f3dico El Ma\u00f1ana de Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=307229|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]|date=12 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> Some witnesses mentioned that they heard grenade explosions during the attack. In addition, a message was reportedly left behind by the perpetrators.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ataca comando peri\u00f3dico 'El Ma\u00f1ana' de Nuevo Laredo; no hay heridos |url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2012/05/12/95952011-ataca-comando-periodico-el-manana-de-nuevo-laredo/ |accessdate=12 May 2012 |newspaper=[[La Jornada]] |date=12 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514023409/http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2012/05/12/95952011-ataca-comando-periodico-el-manana-de-nuevo-laredo |archivedate=14 May 2012 |df=dmy |language=es}}</ref>\n\nThe damage was minimal, but the message was understood. ''El Ma\u00f1ana'' took the attack as a warning from the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] that it wants coverage claiming that they are taking over Nuevo Laredo and beating Los Zetas, therefore making the Sinaloa cartel look \"tough\" and Los Zetas \"look weak.\"<ref name=sinaloazetasmanana>{{cite news|last=O'Conner|first=Mike|title=El Ma\u00f1ana cedes battle to report on Mexican violence|url=http://www.cpj.org/blog/2012/05/el-manana-cedes-battle-to-report-on-mexican-violen.php|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[Committee to Protect Journalists]]|date=23 May 2012}}</ref> The problem is that if the journalists decide to favor the Sinaloa cartel or Los Zetas, they will find themselves threatened by one of the cartels. In other words, one cartel threatens if there isn't coverage (Sinaloa cartel) and the other cartel threatens if there is coverage (Los Zetas).<ref name=sinaloazetasmanana/> Following the attacks, ''[[El Ma\u00f1ana (Nuevo Laredo)|El Ma\u00f1ana]]'' declared that it will no longer report on news relating to [[Mexican Drug War|drug-violence]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Turati|first=Marcela|title=Tras atentado, El Ma\u00f1ana dejar\u00e1 de publicar notas sobre narcoviolencia|url=http://www.proceso.com.mx/?p=307452|accessdate=15 May 2012|newspaper=[[Proceso (magazine)|Proceso]]|date=14 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> They may in fact be the first newspaper to publicly step down and stop covering all crime incidents involving stories of mafia groups fighting for control.<ref name=sinaloazetasmanana/> The day that the editorial stepped down, [[Cadereyta Jim\u00e9nez massacre|49 decapitated bodies]] were found along a highway near Monterrey, Mexico's third largest city, and just 120 miles south of Nuevo Laredo. Most newspapers covered this incident, but ''El Ma\u00f1ana'' did not.<ref name=sinaloazetasmanana/> Again, on 10 June 2012, ''El Ma\u00f1ana'' suffered another grenade attack but only material damages were reported.<ref>{{cite news|title=Three Mexican news outlets targeted in one day|url=http://www.cpj.org/2012/07/three-mexican-news-outlets-targeted-in-one-day.php|accessdate=11 July 2012|newspaper=[[Committee to Protect Journalists]]|date=11 July 2012}}</ref> In response to the attacks, the newspaper issued the following message to the public:\n{{Quotation|We ask for the public's comprehension and will [[Censorship|refrain]], for as long as needed, from publishing any information related to the [[Mexican Drug War|violent disputes]] our city and other regions of the country are suffering ... The company's editorial and administrative board has been forced to make this regrettable decision by circumstances we are all familiar with, and by the lack of adequate conditions for freely exercising professional [[journalism]] ... We will only address the (violent crime) issue through the [[Opinion journalism|opinions]] of professional analysts who study the phenomenon in an intelligent and responsible way ... [We will not] serve the petty interests of any de-facto power or criminal group.<ref>{{cite news|last=[[Ioan Grillo]]|title=Mexico paper stops drug war coverage after grenade attacks|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/07/11/us-mexico-drugs-newspaper-idUSBRE86A1IR20120711|accessdate=12 July 2012|newspaper=[[Reuters]]|date=11 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=El Manana Newspaper To Stop Covering Certain Stories After Second Grenade Attack|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/11/el-manana-newspaper-stories-grenade-attack_n_1664978.html|accessdate=11 July 2012|newspaper=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=11 July 2012}}</ref>}}\nMany Mexicans have been relying on social media chatrooms and sites like Facebook and Twitter as traditional media \"self-censor in the face of cartel violence.\"<ref name=msnblog>{{cite news|title=Blogger on Mexico cartel beheading: Cannot kill us all|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/45230870|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[MSN News]]|date=10 November 2011}}</ref> Moreover, due to the violent attacks the press has received in Nuevo Laredo, news media have practiced \"self-censorship,\" where local journalist prefer to silence the press and refuse to report on important incidents for fears of reprisals by the cartels.<ref name=silence>{{cite news|last=Castillo|first=Mariano|title=Nuevo Laredo media go silent on violence|url=http://www.chron.com/news/nation-world/article/Nuevo-Laredo-media-go-silent-on-violence-1632204.php|accessdate=12 May 2012|newspaper=[[Houston Chronicle]]|date=29 September 2006}}</ref> Events that would go on the front-page of any newspaper\u2014mass murders with over six dead, shooting incidents wounding three soldiers\u2014often go unreported in Nuevo Laredo.<ref name=silence/> The cartels want the cities they control to appear calm in order to prevent the government from sending federal troops.<ref name=silence/> Consequently, the press, tired of extortions and death threats, prefers to go silent because there is no guarantee for their safety.<ref name=silence/>\n\n==Attacks against casinos==\nOn 21 May 2012, the Mexican authorities were alerted that a casino was on fire in Nuevo Laredo. At around six in the morning, an anonymous call alerted the police that smoke was coming from a building.<ref name=casino>{{cite news|title=Se incendia casino en Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas|url=http://www.eluniversal.com.mx/notas/848603.html|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[El Universal (Mexico City)|El Universal]]|date=21 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> By 8:00&nbsp;a.m. the fire had been put down, but a portion of the casino was consumed by the flames.<ref name=casino/> Nonetheless, only material damages were reported.<ref>{{cite news|title=Consume incendio casino clausurado en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2012/05/21/183312201-consume-incendio-casino-clausurado-en-nuevo-laredo|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[La Jornada]]|date=21 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120524045633/http://www.jornada.unam.mx/ultimas/2012/05/21/183312201-consume-incendio-casino-clausurado-en-nuevo-laredo|archive-date=24 May 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all|language=es}}</ref> Inside the casino were several containers holding large amounts of gasoline, which helped the authorities conclude that the arson was intentional.<ref name=casino/> The 'Amazonas' casino, as it was known, opened in February 2010; however, it was closed in March 2012 for operating illegally.<ref name=casino/> According to the ''[[Blog del Narco]]'', several people from Nuevo Laredo knew that the casino was owned by [[Los Zetas]].<ref name=juega/> The article was also mentioned that the Zetas ordered the closure of another casino known as 'El Juega Juega' to benefit 'Amazonas.'<ref name=juega>{{cite news|title=Incendia el casino Amazonas supuestamente de los Zetas en Nuevo Laredo, Tamaulipas|url=http://www.mundonarco.com/2012/05/incendia-el-casino-amazonas.html|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[Blog del Narco]]|date=21 May 2012|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130129090258/http://www.mundonarco.com/2012/05/incendia-el-casino-amazonas.html|archive-date=29 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all|language=es}}</ref>\n\nThree days later on 24 May 2012, the 'Maranho' [[nightclub]], considered among the most popular in Nuevo Laredo, was set on fire between 2:00 and 3:00&nbsp;a.m.<ref>{{cite news|title=Incendian bar y estalla veh\u00edculo en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.animalpolitico.com/2012/05/incendian-bar-y-estalla-vehiculo-en-nuevo-laredo/|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=Animal Politico|date=24 May 2012|language=es}}</ref><ref name=maranho>{{cite news|title=Incendian antro y explotan auto en hotel de Nuevo Laredo|url=http://tamaulipas.milenio.com/cdb/doc/noticias2011/c18034fe3cd5795e5df4a83b70a228ef|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[Milenio]]|date=24 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> And according to unofficial accounts, a group of gunmen were the perpetrators, while some accounts mention that they used grenades and bombs.<ref>{{cite news|title=Reportan ataques en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://noticias.terra.com.mx/mexico/estados/reportan-ataques-en-nuevo-laredo,90ef2a7680087310VgnVCM20000099cceb0aRCRD.html|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[Terra Networks]]|date=24 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> The nightclub was \"completely destroyed,\" but no victims were reported.<ref>{{cite news|title=Se incendia discoteca y explota coche bomba en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://eleconomista.com.mx/seguridad-publica/2012/05/24/se-incendia-discoteca-explota-coche-bomba-nuevo-laredo|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[El Economista (Mexico)|El Economista]]|date=24 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> Other grenade explosions were heard across the border in [[Laredo, Texas]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Incendian discos y granadean hotel en Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.zocalo.com.mx/seccion/articulo/incendian-discos-y-granadean-hotel-en-nuevo-laredo|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=Z\u00f3calo|date=24 May 2012|language=es}}</ref> while the residents turned to #LaredoFollow hashtag on [[Twitter]] to report on the violence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nightclubs burned, chaos in the streets of Nuevo Laredo|url=http://www.valleycentral.com/news/story.aspx?id=757900#.T76iRnlYvDE|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[KGBT-TV]]|date=24 May 2012}}</ref> Unconfirmed reports from [[KGNS-TV]] state that several places in Nuevo Laredo, including educational institutions, are under bomb threats. However, the main targets in the bomb attacks have been entertainment businesses with supposed ties with the mafias that operate in the city.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nuevo Laredo Morning Explosion|url=http://www.pro8news.com/news/local/Nuevo-Laredo-Morning-Explosion--153695805.html|accessdate=24 May 2012|newspaper=[[KGNS-TV]]|date=24 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528115031/http://www.pro8news.com/news/local/Nuevo-Laredo-Morning-Explosion--153695805.html|archive-date=28 May 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Images==\n{{wide image|ElChapoGuzman-gunmen.jpeg|500px|alt=Sinaloa cartel gunmen|Gunmen of the [[Sinaloa Cartel]] in front of a banner directed to members of [[Los Zetas]] based in Nuevo Laredo. The message was allegedly from [[Joaqu\u00edn Guzm\u00e1n Loera]] (\"El Chapo\").}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cadereyta Jim\u00e9nez massacre]]\n* [[2011\u20132012 in the Mexican Drug War]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Mexican Drug War}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nuevo Laredo massacres}}\n[[Category:2012 crimes in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Mexican Drug War]]\n[[Category:Massacres in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 2012]]\n[[Category:Organized crime events in Mexico]]\n[[Category:History of Nuevo Laredo]]\n[[Category:April 2012 events in Mexico]]\n[[Category:May 2012 events in Mexico]]\n[[Category:2012 murders in North America]]\n[[Category:2010s murders in Mexico]]\n", "name_user": "Eschoryii", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e17 April 2012 massacre:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2012_Nuevo_Laredo_massacres"}
